{"title_page": "Greater Sudbury", "text_new": "{{short description|City in Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Greater Sudbury\n|native_name = {{lang|fr|Grand-Sudbury}}\n| official_name         = City of Greater Sudbury<br /><small>''Ville du Grand Sudbury''</small>\n|settlement_type        = [[List of cities in Ontario|City]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Single-tier municipalities|single-tier]])\n|nicknames               = [[List of city nicknames and slogans in Canada#Ontario|\"Nickel Capital\", \"Nickel City\", \"The Big Nickel\" \"City of Lakes\", \"Sudz\"(colloquially)]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/2013/11/17/ukrainians-say-goodbye-to-nickel-city | title=Ukrainians say goodbye to Nickel City | author=Harold Carmichael | newspaper=[[Sudbury Star]] | publisher=[[Canoe Sun Media]] | date=November 18, 2013 | accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Restoring the City of Lakes' aquatic luster|author= Sudbury Northern Life Staff|url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2010/03/freshwater-ecology160310.aspx |newspaper= [[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]|date= March 16, 2010|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n|motto                  = ''Aedificemus''<br /><small>([[Latin]] for \"Come, let us build together\"</small>)\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          = From top left: Downtown Sudbury Skyline, Big Nickel, Bridge of Nations, Inco Superstack, Bell Park, and Science North\n|image_flag             = Flag of Sudbury Ontario.svg\n|flag_size              =\n|image_blank_emblem     = Greater Sudbury logo.svg\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_shield           = Gtsudburycoa.png\n|shield_size            =\n|image_map              = Map of Ontario GREATER SUDBURY.svg\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|pushpin_map            = Canada\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location of Greater Sudbury in Canada\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Canada\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Ontario]]\n|subdivision_type2      =\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      =\n|subdivision_type4      =\n|subdivision_name4      =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           = [[List of mayors of Greater Sudbury|Mayor]]\n|leader_name            = [[Brian Bigger]]\n|leader_title2          = Governing Body\n|leader_name2           = [[Greater Sudbury City Council]]\n|leader_title3          =[[House of Commons of Canada|MPs]]\n|leader_name3           =[[Paul Lefebvre]]&nbsp;([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])<br />[[Marc Serr\u00e9]]&nbsp;([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])\n|leader_title4          =[[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|MPPs]]\n|leader_name4           =[[France G\u00e9linas]]&nbsp;([[Ontario New Democratic Party|NDP]])<br />[[Jamie West]]&nbsp;([[Ontario New Democratic Party|NDP]])\n|established_title      = Founded\n|established_date       = 1883\n|established_title2     = Incorporated (Town)\n|established_date2      = 1893 (as Sudbury)\n|established_title3     = Re-Incorporated (City)\n|established_date3      = 1930 (as Sudbury) \n|established_title4     = &nbsp;\n|established_date4      = 2001 (as Greater Sudbury)\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref              =<!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes         =<ref name=\"Census\"/>\n|area_total_km2         = 3228.35\n|area_land_km2          =\n|area_water_km2         =\n|area_water_percent     =\n|area_urban_km2         = 75.93\n|area_metro_km2         = 3924.48\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_footnotes   =<ref name=\"Census\"/>\n|population_note        =\n|population_total       = {{#statements:P1082|from=Q383434}} ([[List of the 100 largest municipalities in Canada by population|29th]])\n|population_density_km2 = 49.7\n|population_metro       = 164689 ([[List of metropolitan areas in Canada|24th]])\n|population_density_metro_km2 = 49.5\n|population_urban       = 88054<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0904&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&SearchText=Sudbury&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=0904&TABID=1&type=0 |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Sudbury [Population centre], Ontario and Ontario [Province]|publisher = [[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|population_density_urban_km2 = 1159.7\n|timezone               = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = \u221205:00\n|timezone_DST           = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST         = \u221204:00\n|coordinates            = {{coord|46|29|24|N|81|00|36|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 347.5\n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of P postal codes of Canada|P3A to P3G, P3L, P3N, P3P, P3Y]]\n|area_code              =[[Area codes 705 and 249|705/249]]\n|blank_name             = Telephone exchanges\n|blank_info             = ''705''\u2013207, 222, 280, 396, 397, 479, 507, 521, 522, 523, 524, 525, 546, 547, 550, 551, 552, 553, 554, 556, 560, 561, 562, 564, 566, 585, 596, 618, 626, 662, 664, 665, 669, 670, 671, 673, 674, 675, 677, 682, 688, 690, 691, 692, 693, 694, 695, 698, 699, 805, 822, 853, 855, 858, 866, 867, 897, 898, 899, 919, 920, 929, 966, 967, 969, 983\n''249''-810, 878\n|blank2_name             = [[List of highways in Ontario|Highways]]\n|blank2_info             = {{jct|state=ON|Hwy|17|TCH}}<br />{{nowrap|{{jct|state=ON|Hwy|400|TCH}}}}<br />{{jct|state=ON|Hwy|144}}\n|website                = [http://www.greatersudbury.ca/ www.greatersudbury.ca]\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Sudbury''', officially '''Greater Sudbury''' ({{lang-fr|Grand-Sudbury}}), is a city in [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the largest city in [[Northern Ontario]] by population, with a population of 161,531 at the [[2016 Canadian Census]].<ref name=\"Census\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=302&SR=176&S=86&O=A&RPP=25&PR=35&CMA=0&CSD=0 |title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories, and census subdivisions (municipalities), 2016 and 2011 censuses \u2013 100% data|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 6, 2017 |work= |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> By land area, it is the largest in Ontario and the [[List of the 100 largest cities and towns in Canada by area|fifth largest in Canada]]. It is administratively a [[Unitary authority#Canadasingle-tier municipality|Unitary authority]], and thus not part of any district, county, or [[regional municipality]].\n\nThe Sudbury region was inhabited by the [[Ojibwe]] people of the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin group]] for thousands of years prior to the founding of Sudbury following the discovery of [[nickel]] ore in 1883 during the construction of the transcontinental railway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greatersudbury.ca/live/about-greater-sudbury/history/ |title=History - Greater Sudbury |publisher=Greatersudbury.ca |date=2001-01-01 |accessdate=2017-07-26}}</ref> Greater Sudbury was formed in 2001 by merging the cities and towns of the former [[Regional Municipality of Sudbury]] with several previously unincorporated townships. Being located inland, the local climate is extremely seasonal with average January lows of around {{convert|-18|C|0}} and average July highs of {{convert|25|C|0}}.<ref name=\"EnvironmentCanada\" />\n\nThe population resides in an urban core and many smaller communities scattered around 330 lakes and among hills of rock blackened by historical [[smelting]] activity. Sudbury was once a major lumber centre and a world leader in nickel mining. Mining and related industries dominated the economy for much of the 20th century. The two major mining companies which shaped the history of Sudbury were Inco, now [[Vale Limited]], which employed more than 25% of the population by the 1970s, and [[Falconbridge Ltd.|Falconbridge]], now [[Glencore]]. Sudbury has since expanded from its resource-based economy to emerge as the major retail, economic, health and educational centre for Northeastern Ontario. Sudbury is also home to a large [[Franco-Ontarian]] population that influences its arts and culture.\n\n==History==\n<!-- {{Main|History of Sudbury, Ontario}} -->\nThe Sudbury region was inhabited by the [[Ojibwe]] people of the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin group]] as early as 9,000 years ago following the retreat of the last continental ice sheet.<ref name=\"canadianencyclopedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1SEC867615 |title=Sudbury |last=Saarinen |first=O.W. |date=21 October 2012 |publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |access-date=February 3, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211124832/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1SEC867615 |archivedate=December 11, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 1850, a large tract of land, including what is now Sudbury, was signed over to the [[The Crown|British Crown]] by local Ojibwe chiefs as a part of the [[Robinson Treaty#Robinson Huron Treaty|Robinson Huron Treaty]]. In exchange the Crown pledged to pay an annuity to [[First Nations]] people, which was originally set at $1.60 per treaty member and increased incrementally; its last increase was in 1874, leaving it fixed at $4.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manitoulin.ca/judge-rules-robinson-huron-treatys-4-annuity-needs-update/ |title=Judge rules Robinson Huron Treaty\u2019s $4 annuity needs update |first=Michael |last=Erskine |date=9 January 2019 |access-date=10 August 2019 |newspaper=The Manitoulin Expositor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thesudburystar.com/news/local-news/first-nation-in-northern-ontario-win-historic-lawsuit |title=First Nations in Northern Ontario win historic lawsuit |first=Harold |last=Carmichael |newspaper=[[The Sudbury Star]] |date=25 December 2018 |access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrench [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] were the first to establish a European settlement when they set up a [[mission (station)|mission]] called Sainte-Anne-des-Pins, just before the construction of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] in 1883. The Sainte-Anne-des-Pins church played a prominent role in the development of Franco-Ontarian culture in the region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Sudbury03.html |title=Sainte-Anne des Pines |publisher=Ontario's Historical Plaques}}</ref>\n[[File:Sudbury 1888.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] junction in Sudbury in 1888. Construction for the railway led to the discovery of high concentrations of [[nickel]]-[[copper]] [[ore]] at the edge of the [[Sudbury Basin]].]]\nDuring construction of the railway in 1883, blasting and excavation revealed high concentrations of [[nickel]]-[[copper]] [[ore]] at [[Murray Mine]] on the edge of the [[Sudbury Basin]]. This discovery brought the first waves of European settlers, who arrived not only to work at the mines, but also to build a service station for railway workers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.investsudbury.ca/index.php?lang=en&Itemid=222 |title=History |date=2013 |publisher=Greater Sudbury Development Corporation |access-date=February 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208160218/http://www.investsudbury.ca/index.php?lang=en&Itemid=222 |archive-date=February 8, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nJames Worthington, the superintendent of construction on the Northern Ontario segment of the railway, selected the name Sudbury after [[Sudbury, Suffolk]], in England, which was the hometown of his wife Caroline Hitchcock.<ref name=\"canadianencyclopedia\" /><ref>Thomas, Ray and Pearsall, Kathy (1994). ''Sudbury''. Boston Mills Press. {{ISBN|978-1-55046-110-7}}.</ref> Sudbury was incorporated as a town in 1893,<ref>{{cite news |title=History retold through archives |author=Darren MacDonald |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2012/05/04-archive-opening-sudbury.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]] |date= May 3, 2012|access-date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> and its first mayor was Joseph \u00c9tienne aka [[Stephen Fournier]].<ref name = railtown>Wallace, C. M.; & Thomson, Ashley (Eds.) (1993). ''Sudbury: Rail Town to Regional Capital'' (3rd ed.). [[Dundurn Press]]. {{ISBN|978-1-55002-170-7}}.</ref>\n\nThe American inventor [[Thomas Edison]] visited the Sudbury area as a prospector in 1901. He is credited with the original discovery of the ore body at [[Nickel Centre#Falconbridge|Falconbridge]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sudburymuseums.ca/index.cfm?app=w_vmuseum&lang=en&currID=2031&parID=2029 |title=Thomas Edison |website= Greater Sudbury Heritage Museums |publisher=City of Greater Sudbury |access-date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> Rich deposits of [[Millerite|nickel sulphide]] ore were discovered in the [[Sudbury Basin]] geological formation. The construction of the railway allowed exploitation of these mineral resources and shipment of the commodities to markets and ports, as well as large-scale lumber extraction.<ref name=railtown />\n\nMining began to replace lumber as the primary industry as the area's transportation network was improved to include trams. These enabled workers to live in one community and work in another.<ref name=railtown /> Sudbury's economy was dominated by the mining industry for much of the 20th century. Two major mining companies were created: [[Vale Limited|Inco]] in 1902 and [[Falconbridge Ltd.|Falconbridge]] in 1928. They became two of the city's major employers and two of the world's leading producers of nickel.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n[[File:Bird's Eye View of the Smelting Works of the Canadian Copper Co, Ontario (HS85-10-27230).jpg|thumb|left|Smelting works of the Canadian Copper Company prior to [[World War I]]. Most of the nickel mined from Sudbury was used in the manufacturing of artillery during the war.]]\n\nThrough the decades that followed, Sudbury's economy went through boom and bust cycles as world demand for nickel fluctuated. Demand was high during the [[World War I|First World War]], when Sudbury-mined nickel was used extensively in the manufacturing of artillery in [[Sheffield]], England. It bottomed out when the war ended and then rose again in the mid-1920s as peacetime uses for nickel began to develop. The town was reincorporated as a city in 1930.\n\nThe city recovered from the [[Great Depression in Canada|Great Depression]] much more quickly than almost any other city in North America due to increased demand for nickel in the 1930s. Sudbury was the fastest-growing city and one of the wealthiest cities in Canada for most of the decade. Many of the city's social problems in the Great Depression era were not caused by unemployment or poverty, but due to the difficulty in keeping up with all of the new infrastructure demands created by rapid growth \u2014 for example, employed mineworkers sometimes ended up living in [[boarding house]]s or makeshift [[shanty town]]s, because demand for new housing was rising faster than supply.<ref name=railtown /> Between 1936 and 1941, the city was ordered into [[receivership]] by the [[Ontario Municipal Board]].<ref name=railtown /> Another economic slowdown affected the city in 1937, but the city's fortunes rose again with wartime demands during the [[World War II|Second World War]]. The [[Frood Mine]] alone accounted for 40 percent of all the nickel used in [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[artillery]] production during the war. After the end of the war, Sudbury was in a good position to supply nickel to the United States government when it decided to stockpile non-[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] supplies during the [[Cold War]].<ref name=railtown />\n[[File:Banner in Sudbury, Ontario, circa 1942.jpg|thumb|left|Banner welcoming [[Underground mining (hard rock)|hard rock]] miners into Sudbury. Nickel mines became vital to the war effort, with [[Frood Mine]] accounting for 40 percent of all nickel used in [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] artillery production.]]\nThe open coke beds used in the early to mid 20th century and logging for fuel resulted in a near-total loss of native vegetation in the area. Consequently, the terrain was made up of exposed rocky outcrops permanently stained charcoal black by the air pollution from the roasting yards. [[Acid rain]] added more staining, in a layer that penetrates up to {{convert|3|in|abbr=on}} into the once pink-grey [[granite]].\n\nThe construction of the [[Inco Superstack]] in 1972 dispersed sulphuric acid through the air over a much wider area, reducing the acidity of local precipitation. This enabled the city to begin an environmental recovery program. In the late 1970s, private and public interests combined to establish a \"regreening\" effort. [[Calcium oxide|Lime]] was spread over the charred soil by hand and by aircraft. Seeds of wild [[Poaceae|grasses]] and other vegetation were also spread. As of 2010, 9.2&nbsp;million new trees have been planted in the city.<ref>[http://www.greatersudbury.ca/content/div_landreclamation/documents/2010%20Final%20Annual%20Report.pdf Annual Report 2010], City of Greater Sudbury Land Reclamation Program.</ref><!--needs page number--> [[Vale Limited|Vale]] has begun to rehabilitate the [[Spoil tip|slag heap]]s that surrounds their smelter in the Copper Cliff area with the planting of grass and trees,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greatersudbury.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_earthcare&lang=en&currID=6855 |title=Vale Community-based Initiatives |publisher=The City of Greater Sudbury |accessdate=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811013206/http://www.greatersudbury.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_earthcare&lang=en&currID=6855 |archive-date=August 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as the use of [[biosolids]] to stabilize and regreen [[tailings]] areas.<ref>[https://www.northernontariobusiness.com/regional-news/sudbury/biosolids-rejuvenate-mining-wasteland-983489 \"Biosolids rejuvenate mining wasteland\"]. ''[[Northern Ontario Business]]'', July 13, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1978, the workers of Sudbury's largest mining corporation, Inco (now Vale), [[1978 INCO strike|embarked on a strike]] over production and employment cutbacks. The strike, which lasted for nine months, badly damaged Sudbury's economy. The city government was spurred to launch a project to diversify the city's economy. Through an aggressive strategy, the city tried to attract new employers and industries through the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=railtown />\n[[File:Sudbury smokestack 1976.jpg|thumb|The [[Inco Superstack]] in 1976, four years after its completion. It was built to disperse sulphuric acid, and reduce the acidity of local precipitation.]]\nThe city of Sudbury and its suburban communities, which were reorganized into the [[Regional Municipality of Sudbury]] in 1973, was subsequently merged in 2001 into the single-tier city of Greater Sudbury. In 2006, both of the city's major mining companies, Canadian-based Inco and Falconbridge, were taken over by new owners: Inco was acquired by the Brazilian company CVRD (now renamed [[Vale (company)|Vale]]), while Falconbridge was purchased by the Swiss company [[Xstrata]], which itself was purchased by Anglo\u2013Swiss Glencore, forming [[Glencore|Glencore Xstrata]]. Xstrata donated the historic [[Edison Building (Falconbridge)|Edison Building]], the onetime head office of Falconbridge, to the city in 2007 to serve as the new home of the municipal archives.<ref>[http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/pubapps/newsreleases/index.cfm?Release_id=1877&lang=en \"Xstrata Nickel donates building to City of Greater Sudbury for community archives\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928035745/http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/pubapps/newsreleases/index.cfm?Release_id=1877&lang=en |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref> On September 19, 2008, a fire destroyed the historic [[Sudbury Steelworkers Hall]] on Frood Road.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steelworkers Hall goes up in flames |author=Laurel Myers and Heidi Ulrichsen|url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/policeandCourt/2008/091908-fireTOP.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]|date=Sep 19, 2008 |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> A strike at Vale's operations, which began on July 13, 2009, was tentatively resolved in July 2010.<ref>[https://montrealgazette.com/business/Vale+reaches+deal+with+workers+Sudbury+nickel+mine/3237157/story.html \"Vale reaches deal with workers at Sudbury nickel mine\"]{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]'', July 5, 2010.</ref> The 2009 strike lasted longer than the devastating 1978 strike, but had a much more modest effect on the city's economy than the earlier action\u2014unlike in 1978, the local rate of [[unemployment]] ''declined'' slightly during the 2009 strike.<ref>Adam Radwanski, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/adam-radwanski/why-sudbury-is-an-unlikely-magnet-for-global-education/article1680784/ \"Why Sudbury is an unlikely magnet for global education\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', August 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nThe ecology of the Sudbury region has recovered dramatically, helped by regreening programs and improved mining practices. The [[United Nations]] honoured twelve cities in the world, including Sudbury, with the Local Government Honours Award at the 1992 [[Earth Summit]] to recognise the city's community-based environmental reclamation strategies. By 2010, the regreening programs had successfully rehabilitated {{convert|3,350|ha|abbr=on}} of land in the city; however, approximately {{convert|30,000|ha|abbr=on}} of land have yet to be rehabilitated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Regreening: 3,350 hectares done, but 30,000 hectares to go|author= Bill Bradley |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2010/01/regreening260110.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]|date= Jan 25, 2010|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n{{See also|List of lakes in Greater Sudbury}}\nSudbury has 330 lakes over {{convert|10|ha|abbr=on}} within the city limits.<ref name=\"grandsudbury.ca\">{{cite web |url=http://www.grandsudbury.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_lakewaterquality&lang=en&currID=688 |title=City of Lakes |author= City of Sudbury |year=2013|publisher= City of Sudbury |accessdate=12 August 2013}}</ref> The most prominent is [[Lake Wanapitei]], the largest lake in the world completely contained within the boundaries of a single city. [[Ramsey Lake]], a few kilometres south of downtown Sudbury, held the same record before the municipal amalgamation in 2001 brought Lake Wanapitei fully inside the city limits.<ref name=\"grandsudbury.ca\"/> Sudbury is divided into two main watersheds: to the east is the [[French River (Ontario)|French River]] watershed which flows into [[Georgian Bay]] and to the west is the [[Spanish River (Ontario)|Spanish River]] watershed which flows into [[Lake Huron]].<ref name=\"grandsudbury.ca\"/>\n[[File:Wanapitei River.JPG|thumb|left|[[Wanapitei River]] in Sudbury. Located in the [[Great Lakes Basin]], it is a tributary of the [[French River (Ontario)|French River]].]]\nSudbury is built around many small, rocky mountains with exposed [[igneous rock]] of the [[Canadian Shield|Canadian (Precambrian) Shield]]. The ore deposits in Sudbury are part of a large geological structure known as the [[Sudbury Basin]], which are the remnants of a nearly two billion-year-old [[impact crater]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Mountain of a meteor hit ancient Sudbury|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=7ef9efbc-7937-4102-a6a1-21245c546ea5|publisher=The Ottawa Citizen|date=30 August 2007|accessdate=8 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140321062745/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=7ef9efbc-7937-4102-a6a1-21245c546ea5|archivedate=March 21, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> long thought to be the result of a [[meteorite]] collision, more recent analysis has suggested that the crater may in fact have been created by a [[comet]].<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/18/sudbury-basin-comet-impact-crater_n_6168408.html \"Canada's Vast 'Sudbury Basin' Was Created By Comet, Study Says\"]. ''[[Huffington Post]]'', November 18, 2014.</ref>\n\nSudbury's [[pentlandite]], [[pyrite]] and [[pyrrhotite]] ores contain profitable amounts of many elements\u2014primarily nickel and copper, but also platinum, palladium and other valuable metals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ontario.ca/en/about_ontario/004467.html|title=About Ontario|website=Ontario.ca|accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nLocal smelting of the ore releases this sulphur into the atmosphere where it combines with water vapour to form [[Sulfuric acid|sulphuric acid]], contributing to [[acid rain]]. As a result, Sudbury has had a widespread reputation as a wasteland.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/TECH/9609/12/greening.sudbury/ | work=CNN | title=Canadian wasteland gets green makeover}}</ref> In parts of the city, vegetation was devastated by acid rain and logging to provide fuel for early [[smelting]] techniques. To a lesser extent, the area's ecology was also impacted by lumber camps in the area providing wood for the reconstruction of Chicago after the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of 1871. While other logging areas in Northeastern Ontario were also involved in that effort, the emergence of mining related processes in the following decade made it significantly harder for new trees to grow to full maturity in the Sudbury area than elsewhere.<ref name=railtown />\n[[File:Blackened rocks in Sudbury, Ontario.JPG|thumb|Erosion has resulted in [[bedrock]] being exposed in many parts of the city, many of which were charred to a pitted, dark black appearance.]]\nThe resulting erosion exposed [[bedrock]] in many parts of the city, which was charred in most places to a pitted, dark black appearance. There was not a complete lack of vegetation in the region as [[Betula papyrifera|paper birch]] and wild [[blueberry]] patches thrived in the acidic soils. During the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] manned lunar exploration program, [[NASA]] astronauts trained in Sudbury to become familiar with impact [[breccia]] and [[shatter cone]]s, rare rock formations produced by large meteorite impacts. However, the popular misconception that they were visiting Sudbury because it purportedly resembled the lifeless surface of the [[Moon]] persists.<ref>[http://castroller.com/podcasts/TheCurrent/1325020 \"A Mining Town\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708123819/http://castroller.com/podcasts/TheCurrent/1325020 |date=July 8, 2011 }}. ''[[The Current (radio show)|The Current]]'', November 16, 2009.</ref>\n\nThe city's [[Nickel District Conservation Authority]] operates a [[Protected area|conservation area]], the [[Lake Laurentian Conservation Area]], in the city's south end. Other unique environmental projects in the city include the Fielding Bird Sanctuary, a protected area along [[Ontario Highway 17|Highway 17]] near [[Walden, Ontario#Lively|Lively]] that provides a managed natural habitat for birds, and a hiking and nature trail near [[Nickel Centre#Coniston|Coniston]], which is named in honour of scientist [[Jane Goodall]].<ref name=\"sudbury\">{{cite web|url=http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_landreclamation&lang=en&currID=1036|archive-url=https://archive.is/20110728060209/http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_landreclamation&lang=en&currID=1036|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 28, 2011|title=City of Greater Sudbury|date=July 28, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSix [[List of protected areas of Ontario|provincial park]]s ([[Chiniguchi Waterway Provincial Park|Chiniguchi River]], [[Daisy Lake Uplands Provincial Park|Daisy Lake Uplands]], [[Fairbank Provincial Park|Fairbank]], [[Killarney Lakelands and Headwaters Provincial Park|Killarney Lakelands and Headwaters]], [[Lake Wanapitei|Wanapitei]] and [[Windy Lake Provincial Park|Windy Lake]]) and two provincial conservation reserves (MacLennan Esker Forest and Tilton Forest) are also located partially or entirely within the city boundaries.\n\n===Climate===\n\nGreater Sudbury has a [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: ''Dfb''). This region has warm and often hot, humid summers with long, cold and snowy winters. It is situated north of the [[Great Lakes]], making it prone to arctic air masses. Monthly precipitation is equal year round, with snow cover expected six months of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_e.html?stnID=4132&prov=&lang=e&dCode=1&dispBack=1&StationName=sudbury&SearchType=Contains&province=ALL&provBut=&month1=0&month2=12|title=Canadian Climate Normals 1971-2000 Station Data - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|last=Canada|website=climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca}}</ref> Although extreme weather events are rare, [[Sudbury tornado|one of the worst tornadoes]] in Canadian history struck the city and its suburbs on August 20, 1970, killing six people, injuring two hundred, and causing more than [[Canadian dollar|C$]]17 million in damages.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/environment/extreme-weather/extreme-weather-general/freak-tornado-kills-six-in-sudbury.html | work=[[CBC News]] | title=CBC Digital Archives|accessdate= August 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe highest temperature ever recorded in Greater Sudbury was {{convert|41.1|C}} on July 13, 1936.<ref name=\"July 1936\"/> The lowest temperature ever recorded was {{convert|-48.3|C}} on December 29, 1933.<ref name=\"December 1933\"/>\n\n{{Weather box\n| collapsed = yes\n|location = [[Sudbury Airport]], 1981\u22122010 normals, extremes 1887\u2212present{{efn|Extreme high and low temperatures in the table are from Sudbury (June 1887 to July 1930), [[Nickel Centre|Coniston]] (August 1930 to September 1947), Sudbury (October 1947 to January 1954), and [[Sudbury Airport]] (February 1954 to present).}}\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan maximum humidex = 7.1\n|Feb maximum humidex = 10.0\n|Mar maximum humidex = 28.0\n|Apr maximum humidex = 30.7\n|May maximum humidex = 39.4\n|Jun maximum humidex = 41.4\n|Jul maximum humidex = 42.9\n|Aug maximum humidex = 49.2\n|Sep maximum humidex = 38.7\n|Oct maximum humidex = 34.3\n|Nov maximum humidex = 20.0\n|Dec maximum humidex = 17.7\n|year maximum humidex = 49.2\n|Jan record high C = 10.0\n|Feb record high C = 9.4\n|Mar record high C = 25.9\n|Apr record high C = 29.8\n|May record high C = 35.6\n|Jun record high C = 35.7\n|Jul record high C = 41.1\n|Aug record high C = 36.7\n|Sep record high C = 34.4\n|Oct record high C = 27.8\n|Nov record high C = 20.0\n|Dec record high C = 15.6\n|year record high C = 41.1\n|Jan high C = -8.0\n|Feb high C = -5.5\n|Mar high C = 0.4\n|Apr high C = 9.2\n|May high C = 17.0\n|Jun high C = 22.2\n|Jul high C = 24.8\n|Aug high C = 23.4\n|Sep high C = 18.1\n|Oct high C = 10.3\n|Nov high C = 2.6\n|Dec high C = -4.4\n|year high C = 9.2\n|Jan mean C = -13.0\n|Feb mean C = -10.8\n|Mar mean C = -4.9\n|Apr mean C = 3.8\n|May mean C = 11.1\n|Jun mean C = 16.5\n|Jul mean C = 19.1\n|Aug mean C = 18.0\n|Sep mean C = 13.0\n|Oct mean C = 6.0\n|Nov mean C = -1.0\n|Dec mean C = -8.6\n|year mean C = 4.1\n|Jan low C = -17.9\n|Feb low C = -16.0\n|Mar low C = -10.2\n|Apr low C = -1.7\n|May low C = 5.2\n|Jun low C = 10.7\n|Jul low C = 13.4\n|Aug low 