y 1934\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"December 1936\">{{cite web\n| publisher = [[Environment Canada]]\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1921-04-01%7C1976-01-31&mlyRange=1921-01-01%7C1976-12-01&StationID=4112&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnProx&optLimit=specDate&Month=12&Day=1&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&Year=1936&selRowPerPage=25&Line=1&txtRadius=25&optProxType=navLink&txtLatDecDeg=46.483333333333&txtLongDecDeg=80.983333333333&timeframe=2\n| title = December 1936\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"November 1940\">{{cite web\n| publisher = [[Environment Canada]]\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1921-04-01%7C1976-01-31&mlyRange=1921-01-01%7C1976-12-01&StationID=4112&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnProx&optLimit=specDate&Month=11&Day=1&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&Year=1940&selRowPerPage=25&Line=1&txtRadius=25&optProxType=navLink&txtLatDecDeg=46.483333333333&txtLongDecDeg=80.983333333333&timeframe=2\n| title = November 1940\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"July 1941\">{{cite web\n| publisher = [[Environment Canada]]\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1921-04-01%7C1976-01-31&mlyRange=1921-01-01%7C1976-12-01&StationID=4112&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnProx&optLimit=specDate&Month=7&Day=1&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&Year=1941&selRowPerPage=25&Line=1&txtRadius=25&optProxType=navLink&txtLatDecDeg=46.483333333333&txtLongDecDeg=80.983333333333&timeframe=2\n| title = July 1941\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"November 1946\">{{cite web\n| publisher = [[Environment Canada]]\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1921-04-01%7C1976-01-31&mlyRange=1921-01-01%7C1976-12-01&StationID=4112&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnProx&optLimit=specDate&Month=10&Day=1&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&Year=1946&selRowPerPage=25&Line=1&txtRadius=25&optProxType=navLink&txtLatDecDeg=46.483333333333&txtLongDecDeg=80.983333333333&timeframe=2\n| title = November 1946\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"March 1950\">{{cite web\n| publisher = [[Environment Canada]]\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=%7C&dlyRange=1887-06-01%7C1977-09-30&mlyRange=1914-01-01%7C1977-12-01&StationID=4131&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnProx&optLimit=specDate&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&txtRadius=25&optProxType=navLink&txtLatDecDeg=46.466666666667&txtLongDecDeg=80.816666666667&timeframe=2&Year=1950&Month=3\n| title = March 1950\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"March 2012\">{{cite web\n| publisher = [[Environment Canada]]\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_data/daily_data_e.html?hlyRange=1954-01-18%7C2013-03-14&dlyRange=1954-02-01%7C2013-03-14&mlyRange=1954-01-01%7C2013-03-01&StationID=4132&Prov=ON&urlExtension=_e.html&searchType=stnProx&optLimit=specDate&Month=3&Day=1&StartYear=1840&EndYear=2016&Year=2012&selRowPerPage=25&Line=0&txtRadius=25&optProxType=navLink&txtLatDecDeg=46.632247222222&txtLongDecDeg=80.796133333333&timeframe=2\n| title = March 2012\n| work = Canadian Climate Data\n| accessdate = June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n|date=February 2012\n}}\n\n==Administration==\n[[File:159 Cedar Street.jpg|thumb|The head office of the [[Government of Ontario|provincial government]]'s [[Ministry of Northern Development, Mines and Forestry]] is located in Sudbury.]]\n\n===Municipal politics===\nFrom the city hall at [[Tom Davies Square]], the city is headed by twelve [[Greater Sudbury City Council|council]] members and one [[List of mayors of Sudbury, Ontario|mayor]] both elected every four years. The current mayor is [[Brian Bigger]], who was elected in the [[2014 Greater Sudbury municipal election|2014 municipal election]]. The 2011 operating budget for Greater Sudbury was [[Canadian dollar|C$]]471&nbsp;million, and the city employs 2006 full-time workers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greatersudbury.ca/content/div_budget/documents/Budget%202011%20Budget%20Operating%20Summary1.pdf |title=2011 Operating Budget |publisher=Greater Sudbury}}</ref>\n\n===Federal and provincial politics===\nThe city is divided between the federal electoral districts of [[Sudbury (electoral district)|Sudbury]] and [[Nickel Belt]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]], and the provincial electoral districts of [[Sudbury (provincial electoral district)|Sudbury]] and [[Nickel Belt (provincial electoral district)|Nickel Belt]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]]. The federal and provincial districts do not have identical boundaries despite using the same names; most notably, the [[Walden, Ontario|Walden]] district of the city is located in Sudbury federally but in Nickel Belt provincially. The city is represented federally by Members of Parliament [[Paul Lefebvre]] and [[Marc Serr\u00e9]], both of the [[Liberal Party of Canada]], and provincially by [[Jamie West]] and [[France G\u00e9linas]] of the [[Ontario New Democratic Party]]. The provincial [[Ministry of Energy, Northern Development and Mines]] has its head office in the city.\n\nBoth federal and provincial politics in the city tend to be dominated by the Liberal and New Democratic parties. Historically, the Liberals have been stronger in the Sudbury riding, with the New Democrats dominant in Nickel Belt, although both ridings have elected members of both parties at different times.\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Sudbury downtown.JPG|thumb|Downtown Sudbury is the [[central business district]] for Greater Sudbury and one of the many neighbourhoods that make up the city.]]\n{{See also| Urban neighbourhoods of Sudbury }}\nThe city of Sudbury and its suburban communities were reorganized into the [[Regional Municipality of Sudbury]] in 1973, which was subsequently merged in 2001 into the single-tier city of Greater Sudbury.\n\nIn common usage, the city's urban core is still generally referred to as ''Sudbury'', while the outlying former towns are still referred to by their old names and continue in some respects to maintain their own distinct community identities despite their lack of political independence. Each of the seven former municipalities in turn encompasses numerous smaller neighbourhoods. Amalgamated cities (2001 Canadian census population) include: Sudbury (85,354)<ref name=\"www12.statcan.ca\"/> and [[Valley East]] (22,374).<ref>\n{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2001 Community Profile of Valley East | year =2001 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553028&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=valley%20east&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= | accessdate =2012-07-01 }}</ref> Towns (2001 Canadian census population) include: [[Rayside-Balfour]] (15,046),<ref>\n{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2001 Community Profile of Rayside-Balfour | year =2001 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553024&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=rayside-balfour&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= | accessdate =2012-07-01 }}</ref> [[Nickel Centre]] (12,672),<ref>{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2001 Community Profile of Nickel Centre | year =2001 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553001&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Nickel%20Centre&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= | accessdate =2012-07-01 }}</ref> [[Walden, Ontario|Walden]] (10,101),<ref>{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2001 Community Profile of Walden| year =2001 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553012&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=walden&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= | accessdate =2012-07-01 }}</ref> [[Onaping Falls]] (4,887),<ref>{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2001 Community Profile of Onaping Falls| year =2001 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553019&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=onaping%20falls&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= | accessdate =2012-07-01 }}</ref> and [[Capreol]] (3,486).<ref>{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2001 Community Profile of Capreol | year =2001 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553035&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=capreol&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= | accessdate =2012-07-01 }}</ref> The [[Wanup]] area, formerly an unincorporated settlement outside of Sudbury's old city limits, was also annexed into the city in 2001, along with a large wilderness area on the northeastern shore of [[Lake Wanapitei]].\n\n==Culture==\nSudbury's culture is influenced by the large [[Franco-Ontarian]] community consisting of approximately 40 percent of the city's population,<ref name=2011NHS /> particularly in the amalgamated municipalities of [[Valley East]] and [[Rayside-Balfour]] and historically in the [[Urban neighbourhoods of Sudbury#Flour Mill|Moulin-\u00e0-Fleur]] neighbourhood. The French culture is celebrated with the [[Franco-Ontarian flag]], recognized by the province as an official emblem, which was created in 1975 by a group of teachers at [[Laurentian University]] and after some controversy has flown at [[Tom Davies Square]] since 2006. The large francophone community plays a central role in developing and maintaining many of the cultural institutions of Sudbury including the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Nouvel-Ontario]], [[La Nuit sur l'\u00e9tang]], [[La Galerie du Nouvel-Ontario]], [[Le Centre franco-ontarien de folklore]] and the [[Prise de parole]] publishing company. The city hosted Les Jeux de la francophonie canadienne in 2011.\n\n===Arts===\n[[File:ArtGallerySudburyBelrockMansion.jpg|thumb|The [[Art Gallery of Sudbury]] was founded in 1967, and is one of two [[art galleries]] located in the city.]]\nThe Sudbury Arts Council was established in 1974. Its mandate is to connect, communicate and celebrate the arts.<ref>[http://www.thesudburystar.com/2014/03/12/mayor-introduces-new-sudbury-art-event \"Mayor introduces new Sudbury art event\"]. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', March 12, 2014.</ref> It has an important role to provide a calendar of events and news about arts and culture activities. The city is home to two art galleries\u2014the [[Art Gallery of Sudbury]] and [[La Galerie du Nouvel-Ontario]]. Both are dedicated primarily to Canadian art, especially artists from Northern Ontario.\n\nThe city's two professional theatre companies are the anglophone [[Sudbury Theatre Centre]] (STC) and the francophone [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre du Nouvel-Ontario]] (TNO). The STC has its own theatre venue downtown, while the TNO stages its productions at La salle [[Andr\u00e9 Paiement]], a venue located on the campus of [[Coll\u00e8ge Bor\u00e9al]]. Theatre productions are also staged by students at [[Laurentian University]]'s affiliated [[Thorneloe University|Thornloe]] faculty, by a community theatre company at [[Cambrian College]], as well as by high school drama students at [[Sudbury Secondary School]], [[Lo-Ellen Park Secondary School]], [[St. Charles College (Sudbury)|St. Charles College]] and [[\u00c9cole secondaire Macdonald-Cartier]] with its troupe Les Draveurs. Sudbury also has numerous community theatre companies throughout the city, including its first and only for-charity theatre company, UP Theatre.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.uptheatre.com |title = UP Theatre Official Site |accessdate = January 16, 2014 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140110150156/http://uptheatre.com/ |archivedate = January 10, 2014 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Cin\u00e9fest Sudbury International Film Festival]], the city's primary annual film festival, has been staged in September each year since 1989.<ref name=extraseats>\"Extra seats needed at Cinefest\". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', September 27, 1989.</ref> Two smaller specialist film festivals, the [[Junction North International Documentary Film Festival]] for documentary films<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/junction-north-documentary-film-festival-1.4389655 \"Junction North International Documentary Film Festival set for Sudbury\"]. [[CBCS-FM|CBC Sudbury]], November 6, 2017.</ref> and the [[Queer North Film Festival]] for [[LGBT]]-themed films,<ref name=queernorth>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/queer-north-festival-lineup-1.4142217 \"Queer North Film Festival announces lineup for second year\"]. [[CBCS-FM|CBC Sudbury]], June 1, 2017.</ref> are also held each year. Mainstream commercial films are screened at the [[Cineplex Entertainment|SilverCity]] theatre complex, which is also the primary venue for most Cin\u00e9fest screenings. [[Science North]] is home to an [[IMAX]] theatre which screens a program of IMAX films, the Cavern at Science North hosts some gala screenings during Cin\u00e9fest and screens science documentaries during the year, and the Sudbury Indie Cinema programs a repertory cinema lineup of independent and international films as well as organizing both the Junction North and Queer North film festivals.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/indie-cinema-funding-1.4514089 \"New Sudbury Indie Cinema space could leverage more arts and culture\"]. [[CBCS-FM|CBC Sudbury]], February 1, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[Up Here Festival]], launched in 2015, blends a program of musical performance with the creation of both [[mural]]s and [[installation art]] projects throughout the downtown core.<ref>Nick Dunne, [https://www.tvo.org/article/turning-northeastern-ontario-cities-into-outdoor-art-galleries \"Turning northeastern Ontario cities into outdoor art galleries\"]. [[TVOntario]], December 9, 2019.</ref>\n\n====Literature====\nNotable works of literature themed or set primarily or partially in Sudbury or its former suburbs include [[Robert J. Sawyer]]'s ''[[The Neanderthal Parallax]]'' trilogy, [[Alistair MacLeod]]'s novel ''[[No Great Mischief]]'', [[Paul Quarrington]]'s ''[[Logan in Overtime]]'' and [[Jean-Marc Dalp\u00e9]]'s play ''1932, la ville du nickel'' and his short story collection ''Contes sudburois''. The city is also fictionalized as \"Chinookville\" in several books by American comedy writer [[Jack Douglas (writer)|Jack Douglas]], and as \"Complexity\" in [[Tomson Highway]]'s musical play ''[[The (Post) Mistress]]''.<ref name=sudburystar>[http://www.thesudburystar.com/2012/10/25/a-one-of-a-kind-musical \"A one-of-a-kind musical\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308231441/http://www.thesudburystar.com/2012/10/25/a-one-of-a-kind-musical |date=March 8, 2018 }}. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', October 25, 2012.</ref>\n\nNoted writers who have lived in Sudbury include playwrights Jean-Marc Dalp\u00e9, [[Sandra Shamas]] and [[Brigitte Haentjens]], poets [[Robert Dickson (writer)|Robert Dickson]], [[Roger Nash]], [[Gregory Scofield]] and [[Margaret Christakos]], fiction writers [[Kelley Armstrong]], [[Sean Costello (author)|Sean Costello]], [[Sarah Selecky]], [[Matthew Heiti]] and [[Jeffrey Round]], journalist [[Mick Lowe]] and academics [[Richard E. Bennett]], [[Michel Bock]], [[Rand Dyck]], [[Graeme S. Mount]] and [[Gary Kinsman]].\n\n====Music====\n[[File:Melbourne Ska Orchestra.JPG|thumb|The [[Melbourne Ska Orchestra]] performing at the [[Northern Lights Festival Bor\u00e9al]]. Hosted annually in Sudbury, it is Canada's oldest music festival in continuous operation.]]\nSudbury's most successful artists have predominantly been in the country, folk and country-rock genres. These include [[Robert Paquette]], [[Kate Maki]], [[Nathan Lawr]], [[Gil Grand]], [[Kevin Closs]], [[CANO]], [[Jake Mathews]], [[Loma Lyns]], [[Alex J. Robinson]], [[Chuck Labelle]], [[En Bref]] and [[Ox (band)|Ox]]. The [[rap rock]] bands [[Project Wyze]] and [[Konflit|Konflit Dramatik]] were also based in Sudbury. High-profile musicians play at the [[Sudbury Community Arena]]. [[Bell Park (Sudbury)|Bell Park]]'s outdoor Grace Hartman Amphitheatre and [[Laurentian University]]'s Fraser Auditorium are sometimes used for summer bookings. Smaller touring [[indie rock]] bands, as well as some local musicians, are usually booked at The Townehouse Tavern, while local bands play a number of small music venues across the city. The city is also home to annual music festivals including the [[Northern Lights Festival Bor\u00e9al]], the [[Up Here Festival]] and [[La Nuit sur l'\u00e9tang]]. The local [[Sudbury Symphony Orchestra]] performs six annual concerts of [[classical music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sudburysymphony.com/|title=Sudbury Symphony Orchestra - 2015.16 \u2013 Our Sound. Our Symphony.|publisher=|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> Sudbury is also home to the [[Blue Saints Drum and Bugle Corps]], a youth drum corps active since 1952.\n\nOne of [[Stompin' Tom Connors]]' most famous songs, \"[[Sudbury Saturday Night]]\", depicts the hard-drinking, hard-partying social life of [[Underground mining (hard rock)|hard rock miners]] of Sudbury.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mitchell|first=Gillian|title=The North American Folk Music Revival: Nation and Identity in the United States and Canada, 1945-1980|publisher=Ashgate Publishing|year=2007|page=158|isbn=978-0-7546-5756-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XtVapc9Nt8kC&pg=PA158}}</ref> [[Miriam Linna]], who drummed in [[the Cramps]], [[Nervus Rex]] and [[The A-Bones]], was also born in Sudbury.\n\n===Attractions===\n[[File:The Big Nickel at Science North.jpg|thumb|In the early 2000s, the [[Big Nickel]] was temporarily moved to the grounds of [[Science North]] while its original and current site was refurbished into [[Dynamic Earth]].]]\n[[Science North]] is an interactive [[science museum]] and [[Northern Ontario]]'s most popular tourist attraction<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencenorth.ca/about/|title=Science North - About Us - Overview|accessdate=April 9, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309165730/http://www.sciencenorth.ca/about/|archivedate=March 9, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> with around 288,000 visitors per year (as of 2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencenorth.ca/sites/default/files/inline-files/17-18-SN-AR.pdf|title=Science North Annual Report 2017-18|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=City of Timmins|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018091620/http://www.timmins.ca/wp-content/uploads/stc-report.pdf|archivedate=October 18, 2015|access-date=|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It consists of two snowflake-shaped buildings on the southwestern shore of [[Ramsey Lake]] and just south of the city's downtown core. There is also a former [[ice hockey]] arena on-site, which includes the complex's entrance and an [[IMAX]] theatre. The snowflake buildings are connected by a rock tunnel, which passes through a billion-year-old [[Fault (geology)|geologic fault]]. Sudbury's mining heritage is reflected in another major tourist attraction, [[Dynamic Earth]]. This interactive science museum focuses principally on geology and mining history exhibitions and is also home to the [[Big Nickel]], one of Sudbury's most famous landmarks. The city is also home to the [[Greater Sudbury Heritage Museums]], a group of historical community museums, and a mining heritage monument overlooking the city's [[Bell Park (Sudbury)|Bell Park]].\n\nThe [[Inco Superstack]] was the tallest freestanding [[chimney]] in the world at {{convert|380|m|abbr=on}} until the construction of the [[Ekibastuz GRES-2 Power Station]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=1511 |title=INCO Superstack |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |website=skyscraperpage.com |publisher=Skyscraper Source Media|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> and is currently the second tallest structure in Canada after the [[CN Tower]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/?do=country&country=CA |title=CN Tower |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |website=skyscraperpage.com |publisher=Skyscraper Source Media|accessdate=27 August 2013}} Home | CTBUH Skyscraper Center<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It is almost the same height as the roof of the [[Empire State Building]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://skyscraperpage.com/cities/?buildingID=23 |title=Empire State Building|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |website=skyscraperpage.com |publisher=Skyscraper Source Media|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Sudbury Community Arena - Exterior.JPG|thumb|Entrance to the [[Sudbury Community Arena]]. The arena is a multi-purpose arena and the home of the [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]'s [[Sudbury Wolves]].]]\nSudbury has many trails that are used year-round. The Sudbury Trail Plan grooms almost {{convert|1,200|km|abbr=on}} of trails for [[snowmobile]]s in the winter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sudburytrailplan.on.ca/history.php|title=Sudbury Trail Plan Association - History<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=April 9, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111115151836/http://www.sudburytrailplan.on.ca/history.php|archivedate=November 15, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> There are approximately {{convert|200|km|abbr=on}} of non-motorized trails in the City, many of which were built by [[Rainbow Routes Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainbowroutes.com/index.php/routes/|title=Rainbow Routes :: Routes|website=Rainbowroutes.com|access-date=2016-08-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816171913/http://www.rainbowroutes.com/index.php/routes/|archivedate=August 16, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> There is {{convert|23|km|abbr=on}} of diverse hiking, biking, and jogging trails found in the [[Lake Laurentian Conservation Area]] near downtown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontariotrails.on.ca/trails-a-z/lake-laurentian-conservation-area/|title=Lake Laurentian Conservation Area - Ontario Trails Council|publisher=|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> Other trails link Sudbury to areas outside of the city including the [[Trans Canada Trail]], which passes through the city, and the [[Voyageur Hiking Trail]]. The city is also home to [[Sudbury Downs]], a [[harness racing]] track located in [[Rayside-Balfour#Azilda|Azilda]].\n\nThere are a number of sports teams located in the city including the [[Sudbury Wolves]] who play at the [[Sudbury Community Arena]]. The Wolves are an [[ice hockey]] team with the [[Ontario Hockey League]]. The [[Sudbury Spartans]] football club have played in the [[Northern Football Conference]] since 1954.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfcfootball.ca/league-history|title=League History|date=March 30, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> Laurentian University participates in the [[U Sports]] league by the Laurentian Voyageurs and the Laurentian Lady Vees. Cambrian College is represented in the [[Canadian Collegiate Athletic Association]] by the Cambrian Golden Shield, and Coll\u00e8ge Bor\u00e9al is represented by the Bor\u00e9al Vip\u00e8res. High school students compete in the Sudbury District Secondary School Athletic Association (SDSSAA), which is a division of Northern Ontario Secondary School Athletics (NOSSA). The city hosted the [[1980 Pan American Junior Athletics Championships|Pan American Junior Athletics Championships]] in 1980, the [[1988 World Junior Championships in Athletics|IAAF World Junior Championships in Athletics]] in 1988, the [[Tim Hortons Brier|Brier]]: Canada's annual men's [[curling]] championships, in 1953 and 1983, the [[2001 Scott Tournament of Hearts]]: the women's curling championship, and the 2010 Ontario Summer Games.\n\nGreater Sudbury hosts a professional basketball team, the [[Sudbury Five]], who play at the Sudbury Community Arena. The Five are owned by Sudbury Wolves Sports and Entertainment and began play in the [[National Basketball League of Canada]] in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sudbury.com/sports/watch-live-sudburys-pro-basketball-team-unveils-name-logo-this-morning-917939 |title=Introducing Sudbury's pro basketball team ... The Five (no really, that's the name) |publisher=Sudbury.com |access-date=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT community===\n\nZig's, the city's prominent gay business, is the only [[gay bar]] in all of [[Northern Ontario]].<ref>\"Emerging market\". ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', May 1, 2004.</ref> The city has hosted an annual [[Sudbury Pride]] festival since 1997,<ref>[http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2014/07/07-pride-festival-sudbury.aspx \"Sudbury poised to show its pride\"]. ''[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]'', July 7, 2014.</ref> and the Queer North Film Festival was launched in 2016.<ref name=queernorth/> The city's LGBT community has been profiled in two documentary films, the [[Genie Awards|Genie Award]]-winning ''[[Mum's the Word (film)|Mum's the Word]] (Maman et \u00c8ve)'' in 1996<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/lgbt-film-airs-again-1.4158294 \"20 years after Maman et Eve: looking back on coming out in the Nickel City\"]. [[CBCS-FM|CBC Sudbury]], June 13, 2017.</ref> and ''[[The Pinco Triangle]]'' in 1999.<ref>[https://www.dailyxtra.com/steelworkers-miners-faggots-oh-my-48213 \"Steelworkers, miners & faggots. Oh my\"]. ''[[Daily Xtra]]'', May 19, 1999.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|title = Sudbury\n|type = Canada\n|align = right\n|width =\n|state =\n|shading =\n|percentages =\n|footnote = <ref name=\"www12.statcan.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/Profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553007&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Sudbury&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=|title=2001 Community Profiles|website=12.statcan.ca|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n|1901|2027\n|[[Canada 1911 Census|1911]]|4150\n|1921|8621\n|1931|18518\n|1941|31888\n|1951|42410\n|1961|80120\n|1971|90535\n|1981|91829\n|1991|92884\n|[[1996 Canadian Census|1996]]|92059\n|[[2001 Canadian Census|2001]]|85354\n}}\n{{Historical populations\n|title = Greater Sudbury\n|type = Canada\n|align = right\n|width =\n|state =\n|shading =\n|percentages =\n|footnote = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www66.statcan.gc.ca/eng/acyb_c1912-eng.aspx?opt=/eng/1912/191200350011_p.%2011.pdf |title=Canada Year Book 1912 |publisher=Census of Canada |accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Historic_Population_of_Sudbury_Ontario.png|title=English: Historic Population of Sudbury Ontario 1901-2011|first=|last=Mattximus|date=December 20, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=October 21, 2017|via=Wikimedia Commons}}</ref>\n|[[2001 Canadian Census|2001]]|155219\n|[[2006 Canadian Census|2006]]|157857\n|[[2011 Canadian Census|2011]]|160274\n|[[2016 Canadian Census|2016]]|161531\n}}\nGreater Sudbury is the most populous municipality and [[Census geographic units of Canada#Census metropolitan areas|census metropolitan area]] in [[Northern Ontario]]. In the 2016 census, the city's population increased to 161,531, a growth of 0.8 per cent over the 2011 population of 160,274. The median age is 41.1 years, slightly higher than the provincial average of 39.0 years.<ref name=\"www12.statcan.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-591/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553005&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=greater%20sudbury&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=|title=Statistics Canada: 2006 Community Profiles|first=Government of Canada, Statistics|last=Canada|publisher=|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> The census metropolitan area of Greater Sudbury (population 164,770) consists of the city, the town of [[Markstay-Warren]] and the adjacent [[First Nations]] [[Indian reserve|reserves]] of [[Wahnapitae First Nation|Wahnapitei]] (population 116) and [[Whitefish Lake 6, Ontario|Atikameksheng Anishnawbek]] (population 386), formerly known as Whitefish Lake. As the Wahnapitei First Nation is an enclave within the city boundaries, it is also counted as part of Greater Sudbury's [[List of census divisions of Ontario|census division]] population of 161,647; this figure excludes Atikameksheng and Markstay-Warren, which are counted as part of the separate [[Sudbury District]].\n\nIn the 2016 census, eight distinct \"population centres\", or [[urban area]]s, were listed within the city: Sudbury (population 88,054), comprising the main populated core of the old city of Sudbury and the neighbourhood of Garson in the former town of Nickel Centre; Azilda (population 4,663); Capreol (population 2,815); Chelmsford (population 6,215); Coniston (population 1,814); Dowling (population 1,466); Lively (population 5,608); and Valley East (population 17,451). In total, these population centres have 128,086 residents, or 79 per cent of the city's total population. The remaining 21 per cent of the city's population live in more rural areas within the city limits for which distinct population statistics were not published separately from those for the city as a whole.\n\nSudbury is a bilingual city with a large [[French language in Canada|francophone]] population, with 40% of Sudburians able to speak French. Some 80.1% of the population speak mostly English at home, followed by French at 16.3%, which is higher than the Ontario average of 2.4%.<ref>{{cite web|last=Statistics Canada|title =2006 Community Profile | year =2006 |url =http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-591/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553005&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=greater%20sudbury&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= |accessdate =2011-08-28}}</ref> According to the 2011 National Household Survey, the residents of Greater Sudbury are predominantly Christian. Around 81% (down from 90% in 2001)<ref>{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2001 Community Profile | year =2001 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553005&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Sudbury&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom= | accessdate =2007-09-05 }}</ref> of the population belongs to Christian denominations with a Roman Catholic majority (59%, down from 65% in 2001).<ref name=\"Statistics Canada 2011\">{{cite web| last =Statistics Canada | title =2011 National Household Survey | year =2011 | url = http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553005&Data=Count&SearchText=greater%20sudbury&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 | accessdate =2013-08-30}}</ref> Those with no religious affiliation accounted for 18% (up from 9.9% in 2001) of the population.<ref name=\"Statistics Canada 2011\"/> Other religions such as Islam, Judaism, and [[Hinduism]] constitute around one per cent of the population.<ref name=\"Statistics Canada 2011\"/>\n\nGreater Sudbury has few visible minorities with {{percent|5,990|158,665|1}} reporting visible minority status on the 2016 census compared to the national average of {{percent|7,674,580|34,460,065|1}}, but a much higher percentage of indigenous Canadians ({{percent|19,785|158,665|1}}) compared to the national average of {{percent|2,130,520|34,460,065|1}}. Visible minorities representing over 0.5% of the population include: 0.9% [[South Asian Canadians|South Asian]], 0.9% [[Black Canadians|Black]], and 0.6% [[Chinese Canadians|Chinese]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3553&SearchText=greater+sud&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=1|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - Greater Sudbury, City [Census subdivision], Ontario and Greater Sudbury, Census division [Census division], Ontario|last=Government of Canada|first=Statistics Canada|date=2017-02-08|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2011, the population of Sudbury is less educated than the Canadian average, with 17.2% of the population holding a university degree (compared to 23.3% nationally) and 18.1% with no certificate, diploma or degree (compared to 17.3% nationally).<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/as-sa/fogs-spg/Pages/FOG.cfm?lang=E&level=3&GeoCode=580|title=Greater Sudbury / Grand Sudbury (CMA) - Focus on Geography Series - 2011 National Household Survey (NHS)|last=Canada|first=Government of Canada, Statistics|publisher=|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Sudbury\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=left\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Catholic Church|Catholic Christian]]|blue|59}}\n{{bar percent|[[Protestantism|Protestant Christians]]|orange|21}}\n{{bar percent|[[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christians]]|purple|1}}\n{{bar percent|Non-affiliated|green|18}}\n{{bar percent|Others|black|1}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions (2011 NHS)\n}}\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\"\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{|\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n|+Reported Ethnic Origins, 2016\n! Ethnic origin\n! Population<ref name=\"2011NHS\">{{cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3553005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3553&SearchText=greater+sud&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=1|title=Greater Sudbury, City [Census subdivision], Ontario and Greater Sudbury, Census division [Census division], Ontario|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|year=2013|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=12 August 2013}}\n</ref>\n! Percent<ref group=\"note\">Note that a person may report more than one ethnic origin.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Canadians|Canadian]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"|72,315\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |45.6\n|-\n| [[French Canadians|French]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"|59,885\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |37.7\n|-\n| [[English Canadians|English]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"|31,790\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |20.0\n|-\n| [[Irish Canadians|Irish]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"|30,345\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |19.1\n|-\n| [[Scottish Canadians|Scottish]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"|24,990\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |15.8\n|-\n|[[Italian Canadians|Italian]]|| style=\"text-align:right;\" |13,420\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" |8.5\n|}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n{|\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n|+Reported Ethnic Origins, 2016\n! Ethnic origin\n! Population\n! Percent\n|-\n|[[German Canadians|German]]|| style=\"text-align:right;\" |12,905\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 8.1\n|-\n| [[First Nations]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"|10,985\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 6.9\n|-\n| [[M\u00e9tis in Canada|M\u00e9tis]]|| style=\"text-align:right;\" |8,995\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 5.7\n|-\n| [[Ukrainian Canadians|Ukrainian]]|| style=\"text-align:right;\" |7,390\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 4.7\n|-\n| [[Finnish Canadians|Finnish]]|| style=\"text-align:right;\" |7,365\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 4.6\n|-\n| [[Polish Canadians|Polish]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"|4,815\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 3.0\n|}\n|}\n|-\n|{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Economy==\n{{See also|Economy of Greater Sudbury|Timeline of labour in Greater Sudbury}}\n[[File:Copper Cliff South Mine.JPG|thumb|The [[Copper Cliff South Mine]] is an underground nickel mine operated by [[Vale Inco]]. As of 2010, Vale was the largest employer in Greater Sudbury.]]\n[[File:City view (5669653426).jpg|thumb|Barry Downe Road in Sudbury, with several businesses in the [[Tertiary sector of the economy|service sector]] visible. By 2006, 80 percent of Greater Sudbury's labour force was employed in the service sector.]]\nAfter a brief period as a lumber camp, Sudbury's economy was dominated by the mining industry for much of the 20th century. By the 1970s, Inco employed a quarter of the local workforce.<ref name=restive>[https://www.thestar.com/business/article/740849--in-sudbury-it-s-restive-not-festive \"In Sudbury it's restive, not festive\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', December 19, 2009.</ref> However, in 2006, Inco and Falconbridge were taken over by foreign multinational corporations: Inco was acquired by the Brazilian company [[Vale (company)|Vale]], and Falconbridge was purchased by the Swiss company [[Xstrata]] which was in turn purchased by Anglo\u2013Swiss Glencore forming [[Glencore|Glencore Xstrata]]. Several other mining companies, including First Nickel and [[KGHM Polska Mied\u017a|KGHM]], also have mining operations in the Sudbury area.\n\nMining now employs only 6,000 people in the city, although the mining supply and service sector employs a further 10,000.<ref name=\"PricewaterhouseCoopers\"/> By 2006, 80% of Greater Sudbury's labour force was employed in services with 20% remaining in manufacturing.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} Over 345 mining supply and service companies are located in Sudbury.<ref>[http://www.republicofmining.com/2008/06/06/sudbury-north-bay-supply-corridor-growing-dick-destefano/#more-274 \"Sudbury-North Bay mining supply corridor growing\"]. ''[[Sudbury Mining Solutions Journal]]'', June 6, 2008.</ref> This includes a number of public and private firms pursuing research and development in new mining technologies such as [[Mining Innovation Rehabilitation and Applied Research Corporation]] (MIRARCO), the [[NORCAT|Northern Centre for Advanced Technology (NORCAT)]], and the [[Centre for Excellence in Mining Innovation]] (CEMI).<ref name=\"snoplus.phy.queensu.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://snoplus.phy.queensu.ca/Home.html|title=SNO+|website=Snoplus.phy.queensu.ca|accessdate=October 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711152439/http://snoplus.phy.queensu.ca/Home.html|archive-date=July 11, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nWhile mining has decreased in relative importance, Sudbury's economy has diversified to establish itself as a major centre of finance, business, tourism, health care, education, government, and science and technology research.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ontario.ca/en/about_ontario/004664.html |title=Greater Sudbury |accessdate=2017-08-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414183749/http://www.ontario.ca/en/about_ontario/004664.html |archivedate=April 14, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Many of these reflect Sudbury's position as a regional service centre for [[Northeastern Ontario]], a market of 550,000 people.<ref name=\"PricewaterhouseCoopers\"/>\n\nThe top employers in Sudbury as of November 2010 include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatersudbury.ca/keyfacts/index.cfm?app=keyfacts&lang=en&ct=352&items=&sr=&cntid=1047|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210232648/http://www.greatersudbury.ca/keyfacts/index.cfm?app=keyfacts&lang=en&ct=352&items=&sr=&cntid=1047|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 10, 2010|title=Keyfacts|date=December 10, 2010|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Company / organization\n! Employees\n! Sector\n|-\n| [[Vale Limited|Vale]]||4,000||Mining\n|-\n| [[Health Sciences North]] ||3,700||Health services\n|-\n| [[Canada Revenue Agency|Sudbury Tax Services Office]]||2,800||Federal government\n|-\n| City of Greater Sudbury||2,166||Municipal government\n|-\n| [[Laurentian University]]||1,850||Education\n|-\n| [[Rainbow District School Board]]||1,606||Education\n|-\n| [[Government of Ontario|Ontario Ministries and Agencies]] ||1,500||Ontario government\n|-\n| [[Conseil scolaire catholique du Nouvel-Ontario]]||1,443||Education\n|-\n| [[Xstrata]]||1,139||Mining\n|}\n\nMany retail businesses in the city have moved outside of the downtown core in the late 20th century and the city has struggled to rebuild and maintain a vibrant downtown core. In the 2000s and early 2010s, projects aimed at revitalizing the downtown core included the creation of Market Square, a farmer's and craft market; the redevelopment of the Rainbow Centre Mall; streetscape beautification projects; the conversion of several underutilized [[List of historic places in Greater Sudbury|historic properties]] into [[mixed-use development|mixed-use]] office and [[loft]] developments;<ref name=developers>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/story/2012/12/10/sby-downtown-building-renovations.html \"Sudbury developers tackle old downtown buildings\"]. [[CBC News]], December 10, 2012.</ref> and the establishment and launch of the [[McEwen School of Architecture]], as well as cultural events such as Downtown Rotary Blues for Food, Sudbury's Largest Yard and Sidewalk Sale, Downtown Sudbury Ribfest and the Up Here art and music festival. New projects underway in the late 2010s include Place des Arts, a performing and visual arts centre;<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/place-des-arts-funding-1.4625176 \"Place des Arts receives $250K boost from Desjardins\"]. [[CBCS-FM|CBC Sudbury]], April 18, 2018.</ref> the redesign and renovation of the central plaza at [[Tom Davies Square]];<ref name=bids>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/tom-davies-square-courtyard-overbudget-1.4052436 \"Bids for Tom Davies courtyard redesign come in millions over budget\"]. [[CBCS-FM|CBC Northern Ontario]], April 3, 2017.</ref> and the creation of The Junction, a multi-use complex which will incorporate the new home of the [[Art Gallery of Sudbury]], the new main branch of the [[Greater Sudbury Public Library]], and a convention and performance theatre space.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/junction-sudbury-downtown-art-gallery-library-centre-1.4619447 \"Sudbury manager says 'The Junction' works on many levels to describe future downtown site\"]. [[CBCS-FM|CBC Sudbury]], April 16, 2018.</ref>\n\nDespite these efforts a large percentage of the city's retail service sector is still found outside of the downtown core, in areas such as the Four Corners, the RioCan and Silver Hills [[Retail park|power centre]]s on the Kingsway, and the [[New Sudbury Centre]], the largest shopping mall in [[Northern Ontario]] with 110 stores.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsudburycentre.ca/leasing.html|title=Leasing|website=Newsudburycentre.ca|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n=== Local Business ===\n'''Sudbury Massages''' - Offering Sudbury and surrounding areas with exceptional massages and [https://www.sudburymassages.com/ massage therapy] treatments! Our clinic is managed locally in Sudbury and massages are performed by a registered massage therapist. Amazing Massage Therapy Near Me? No Need To Ask That Anymore! We specialize in Registered Massage Therapy, Osteopathy, Manual Therapy and Bioflex Laser treatment .\n\n===Film industry===\nSudbury has an emerging film and television industry, with a number of projects filming in the city in the 2000s.<ref name=hollywood>[http://www.news1130.com/2015/06/25/hollywood-further-north-sudbury-ont-becoming-hot-spot-for-film-crews/ \"Hollywood (Further) North? Sudbury, Ont., becoming hot spot for film crews\"]. [[Canadian Press]], June 25, 2015.</ref> Development of an active film and television production industry in Northern Ontario was initially undertaken by [[Cin\u00e9fest Sudbury International Film Festival|Cin\u00e9fest]], the city's annual film festival, in the early 1990s, and is currently overseen by Music and Film in Motion, a non-profit organization based in Sudbury.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130204112312/http://www.thesudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3088605 \"Landry leaving Music and Film in Motion\"]. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', April 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nFilms shot in the city have included ''[[Roadkill (1989 film)|Roadkill]]'',<ref name=roadkill>{{cite web|url=http://tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/films/roadkill|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130222152040/http://tiff.net/CANADIANFILMENCYCLOPEDIA/content/films/roadkill|url-status=dead|title=Canadian Film Encyclopedia - Roadkill|date=February 22, 2013|archivedate=February 22, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Shania: A Life in Eight Albums]]'',<ref>[http://www.baytoday.ca/content/editorials/details.asp?c=10314 \"CBC to premiere \u201cShania: A Life in Eight Albums\u201d\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819084505/http://www.baytoday.ca/content/editorials/details.asp?c=10314 |date=August 19, 2014 }}. ''Bay Today'', November 2, 2005.</ref> ''[[A Dark Truth|The Truth]]'', ''[[The Lesser Blessed]]'',<ref name=cbc>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2012/10/22/lesser-blessed-imaginative-charleyboy.html \"The Lesser Blessed tells universal story of alienation\"]. [[CBC News]], October 22, 2012.</ref> ''[[High Chicago]]'',<ref>[http://www.thesudburystar.com/2012/04/14/filmmaker-favours-sudbury-for-filming \"Filmmaker favours Sudbury for filming\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829075848/http://www.thesudburystar.com/2012/04/14/filmmaker-favours-sudbury-for-filming |date=August 29, 2017 }}. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', April 15, 2012.</ref> ''[[Perspective (film)|Perspective]]'', ''[[The Captive (2014 film)|The Captive]]'',<ref>[http://www.thesudburystar.com/2013/03/01/egoyan-film-gets-1-million-from-nohfc \"Egoyan film gets $1 million from NOHFC\"]. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', 1 March 2013.</ref> ''[[Ice Soldiers]]'',<ref>\"New era in Canadian film possible; Gunnarsson laments the state of feature filmmaking in this country\". ''[[Vancouver Sun]]'', January 24, 2014.</ref> ''[[Born to Be Blue (film)|Born to Be Blue]]'',<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/ethan-hawke-shoots-chet-baker-biopic-in-sudbury-1.2810212 \"Ethan Hawke shoots Chet Baker biopic in Sudbury\"]. [[CBC News]], October 23, 2014.</ref> ''[[Your Name Here (2015 film)|Your Name Here]]'', ''[[Indian Horse (film)|Indian Horse]]'',<ref>[http://playbackonline.ca/2016/11/25/cameras-roll-on-indian-horse/ \"Production underway on Indian Horse\"]. ''[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]'', November 25, 2016.</ref> ''[[The New Romantic]]''<ref>[http://playbackonline.ca/2017/11/06/inside-independent-edges-new-romantics/ \"Inside Independent Edge\u2019s New Romantic\"]. ''[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]'', November 6, 2017.</ref> and ''[[Men with Brooms]]''.<ref name=hollywood/> Television series filmed in the city include ''[[M\u00e9t\u00e9o+]]'',<ref>[http://www.northernlife.ca/News/Lifestyle/2007/06-18-07-actors.asp?NLStory=06-18-07-actors \"TFO to film French-language comedy in Greater Sudbury\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231555/http://www.northernlife.ca/News/Lifestyle/2007/06-18-07-actors.asp?NLStory=06-18-07-actors |date=March 3, 2016 }}, ''[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]'', June 18, 2007.</ref> ''[[Les Bleus de Ramville]]'',<ref name=\"ramville\">[http://news.ontario.ca/mndmf/en/2010/05/new-tv-series-produced-in-sudbury-and-area.html New TV Series Produced In Sudbury And Area] Government of Ontario, May 21, 2010.</ref> ''[[Hard Rock Medical]]'',<ref>{{cite news |title= New TV show inspired by northern medical school|author=Heidi Ulrichsen |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localnews/2011/12/09-hard-rock-medical-sudbury.aspx|newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]] |date=Dec 9, 2011 |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> ''[[Dark Rising|Dark Rising: Warrior of Worlds]]'',<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/story/2012/07/13/sby-series-filming.html \"Film shoot causes conflict with biz owner\"]. [[CBC News]], July 13, 2012.</ref> ''[[Letterkenny (TV series)|Letterkenny]]'',<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/05/26/jared-keeso-series-letterkenny-shooting-in-sudbury.html \"Jared Keeso series Letterkenny shooting in Sudbury\"]. ''Toronto Star'', May 26, 2015.</ref> ''[[St. Nickel]]'',<ref name=stnickel>[http://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/06/25/st-nickel-unis-tv-premiere-serie-originale_n_7664960.html \"\u00abSt-Nickel\u00bb: une premi\u00e8re s\u00e9rie originale pour Unis TV\"]. ''[[Huffington Post]]'', June 25, 2015.</ref> ''[[Cardinal (TV series)|Cardinal]]'',<ref name=broadcaster>[http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/ctv-and-super-ecran-partner-on-new-serialized-drama/1004021569/ \"CTV and Super \u00c9cran Partner on New Serialized Drama\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215172722/http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/ctv-and-super-ecran-partner-on-new-serialized-drama/1004021569/ |date=February 15, 2016 }}. ''Broadcaster'', February 11, 2016.</ref> ''[[What Would Sal Do?]]''<ref>[http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/super-channel-announces-start-of-production-on-original-scripted-comedy-series/1003768209/ \"Super Channel Announces Start of Production on Original Scripted Comedy Series\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305031836/http://www.broadcastermagazine.com/news/super-channel-announces-start-of-production-on-original-scripted-comedy-series/1003768209/ |date=March 5, 2016 }}. ''Broadcaster'', August 19, 2015.</ref> and ''[[Bad Blood (TV series)|Bad Blood]]''.<ref name=mtlgazette>[https://montrealgazette.com/entertainment/rizzuto-the-tv-series-on-a-tv-screen-near-you-in-fall-2017 \"Montreal Mafia TV series coming to a screen near you in fall 2017\"]. ''[[Montreal Gazette]]'', January 12, 2017.</ref> [[March Entertainment]]'s studio in Sudbury has produced a number of animated television series, including ''[[Chilly Beach]]'', ''[[Maple Shorts]]'', ''[[Yam Roll]]'', and ''[[Dex Hamilton: Alien Entomologist]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title= NOHFC invests $2.5 million in animation studio|author=Arron Pickard |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2011/12/02-NOHFC-invests-in-March-Ent-Sudbury.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]] |date=Dec 2, 2011 |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nSudbury is also home to the [[Science North Production Team]], an award-winning producer of documentary films and multimedia presentations for museums.<ref>{{cite news |title=Science North fired up over award |author=Sudbury Northern Life Staff |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2012/05/07-science-north-wildfire-award-sudbury.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]] |date=May 7, 2012 |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> [[Independent film]]maker [[B. P. Paquette]] and producer Jason Ross Jallet are based in Sudbury.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120722043500/http://sudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?archive=true&e=1210032 \"Film company has big plans for Sudbury\"]. ''The Sudbury Star'', September 20, 2008.</ref> Inner City Films, a production company owned by Sudbury native [[Robert Adetuyi]], also has a production office in the city,<ref name=boosting>{{cite news |title=Boosting home-grown film |author=Sudbury Northern Life Staff |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2010/07/sudbury-film290710.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]] |date=Jul 28, 2010 |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> as does Carte Blanche Films, the producer of ''M\u00e9t\u00e9o+'', ''Les Blues de Ramville'' and ''Hard Rock Medical''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Greater Sudbury is stage for hockey drama |author=Jenny Jelen |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/lifestyle/2011/02/ramville-070211.aspx |newspaper= [[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]|date=Feb 7, 2011 |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\n[[File:NOSMexterior.jpg|thumb|The [[Northern Ontario School of Medicine]] at [[Laurentian University]].The bilingual institution (English and French) is the only university in Sudbury.]]\nGreater Sudbury is home to three postsecondary institutions: [[Laurentian University]], a primarily undergraduate bilingual university with approximately 9,000 students,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laurentian.ca/Laurentian/Home/About+LU/Welcome+-+About+LU.htm?Laurentian_Lang=en-CA|title=Welcome - About LU|date=September 25, 2008|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925065206/http://www.laurentian.ca/Laurentian/Home/About+LU/Welcome+-+About+LU.htm?Laurentian_Lang=en-CA|archivedate=September 25, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Cambrian College]], an English college of applied arts and technology with 4,500 full-time and 7,500 part-time students,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cambriancollege.ca/AboutCambrian/Pages/AboutCambrian.aspx |title=About Cambrian |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |website=Cambriancollege.ca |publisher=[[Cambrian College]] |accessdate=12 August 2013}}</ref> and [[Coll\u00e8ge Bor\u00e9al]], a francophone college with 2,000 enrolled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collegeboreal.ca/student-services/college-life/ |title=College life |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |website=Collegeboreal.ca |publisher=[[Coll\u00e8ge Bor\u00e9al]] |accessdate=12 August 2013}}</ref> Laurentian University is home to the Sudbury campus of the [[Northern Ontario School of Medicine]]. NOSM was the first medical school to be established in Canada in 30 years, having opened in September 2005. On September 4, 2013, Laurentian opened the [[McEwen School of Architecture]] in downtown Sudbury\u2014the first new architecture school to launch in Canada in more than 40 years.<ref>[http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2013/09/05-architecture-school-opening-sudbury.aspx \"'Dream project' architecture school opens its doors\"]. ''[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]'', September 5, 2013.</ref> Canadian post-secondary institutions have also impacted the city's science and technology sectors. The Creighton Mine site in Sudbury is home to [[SNOLAB]], the second-deepest (after [[China Jinping Underground Laboratory]] in China) underground laboratory in the world and the site of numerous [[dark matter]] experiments. Originally constructed for the [[Sudbury Neutrino Observatory]] (now concluded), the underground laboratory has been expanded and continues to operate as SNOLAB. The SNO equipment has been refurbished for use in the [[SNO+]] experiment.{{r|snoplus.phy.queensu.ca}}\n[[File:SNOLAB 2014-03-21.jpg|thumb|left|[[SNOLAB]] is an underground physics laboratory operated by several universities, including Laurentian.]]\nEnglish-language public schooling is provided by the [[Rainbow District School Board]]. The board operates 27 elementary and seven secondary schools in Sudbury, one school for students with special needs, and the Cecil Facer Youth Centre for young offenders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainbowschools.ca/schools/schoolsDirectory.php|title=Directory of Schools - Rainbow District School Board|publisher=|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> The [[Sudbury Catholic District School Board]] offers publicly funded English-language Catholic education, with 20 elementary schools, four high schools and an adult education centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scdsb.edu.on.ca/schools/schools.php|title=Sudbury Catholic Schools - List of Schools|accessdate=April 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410051516/http://www.scdsb.edu.on.ca/schools/schools.php|archive-date=April 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> French-language public schools are administered by the [[Conseil scolaire de district du Grand Nord de l'Ontario]] with seven elementary and two secondary schools and one alternative secondary school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cspgno.ca/|title=Conseil scolaire public du Grand Nord de l\u2019Ontario|publisher=|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref> Finally, the [[Conseil scolaire catholique du Nouvel-Ontario]] provides publicly funded French-language Catholic education, with 15 elementary, four secondary schools, and one adult education secondary school.{{dead link|date=August 2013}}<ref>[http://www.nouvelon.ca/nos_ecoles/index.php Le Conseil scolaire de district catholique du Nouvel-Ontario<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327183332/http://www.nouvelon.ca/nos_ecoles/index.php |date=March 27, 2012 }}</ref> There are also two Christian private schools (Glad Tidings Academy and King Christian Academy), as well two Montessori schools (King Montessori Academy and the Montessori School of Sudbury).\n\nThe [[Greater Sudbury Public Library]] system has 13 branches throughout the city. The library system had 600 thousand items as of 2011 and over 50% of the resident population are active library users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sudburylibraries.ca/en/aboutus/resources/StrategicPlan.pdf|format=PDF|title=Library Services Strategic Plan|website=Sudburylibraries.ca|accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref> The Sudbury Tool Library and Makerspace are located at the main branch of the Greater Sudbury Public Library.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Health care===\nGreater Sudbury serves as the health care centre for much of northeastern Ontario through [[Health Sciences North]]. Sudbury is also the site of the Regional Cancer Program, which treats cancer patients from across the north. In 1968, the first successful [[coronary artery bypass surgery]] in Canada was performed at Sudbury Memorial Hospital.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pioneer cardiac interventionist retiring |url=https://www.thesudburystar.com/2016/04/26/pioneer-cardiac-interventionist-retiring/wcm/a5c8c685-feff-be97-8f1d-bf049e0bda27 |publisher=The Sudbury Star |accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> Adult mental health services are also provided to the area through Health Sciences North, primarily at the Kirkwood site (formerly the Sudbury Algoma Hospital) and at the Cedar site downtown. Children's mental health services are provided through the Regional Children's Psychiatric Centre operated by the Northeast Mental Health Centre, located onsite at the Kirkwood Site of Health Sciences North.\n\n===Emergency services===\nGreater Sudbury is served by the [[Greater Sudbury Police Service]],<ref>{{cite web | coauthors = | title =Greater Sudbury Police Service | url =http://www.police.sudbury.on.ca/ | accessdate = 2007-09-06 }}</ref> headquartered in downtown Sudbury. There is also a detachment of the [[Ontario Provincial Police]] located in the McFarlane Lake area of the city's south end. Greater Sudbury Emergency Medical Services provides prehospital paramedic services with over 150 full-time and part-time paramedics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_ems&lang=en&currID=3077 |title= Ambulance - About Us |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=City.greatersudbury.on.ca |publisher=City of Sudbury |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> Greater Sudbury Fire Services operates from 24 fire stations located throughout the city,<ref>{{cite news |title=Fire services reviewing efficiencies |author=Arron Pickard |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2012/04/09-fire-services-review-sudbury.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]] |date=9 April 2012 |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> with a combination 103 career staff and 350 volunteer fire fighters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_fireservices&lang=en |title= Fire Services - About Us |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=City.greatersudbury.on.ca |publisher=City of Sudbury |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref> Prior to the municipal amalgamation of 2001, most of the suburban towns were served by separate [[volunteer fire department]]s, which were amalgamated into the citywide service as part of the municipal restructuring. The municipally owned energy provider [[Greater Sudbury Utilities]] serves the city's urban core, while rural areas in the city continue to be served by [[Hydro One]].\n\n===Transportation===\n\n====Public transportation====\n\nThe city maintains a bus-based [[public transport|public transit]] system, [[GOVA]], transporting 4.4 million passengers in 2012.<ref name=\"PricewaterhouseCoopers\">{{cite book |last= |first= |authorlink= |title=City of Greater Sudbury Annual Financial Report For the year ended December 31, 2012 |url=http://www.greatersudbury.ca/sudburyen/assets/File/2012%20Annual%20Financial%20Report(1).pdf |accessdate= August 14, 2013 |year=1013 |publisher= [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]]|location= |isbn= |page=1}}</ref> The year 2000 marked the most significant change in Greater Sudbury's local transit history, as outlying townships were annexed into the municipality to form Greater Sudbury, expanding Greater Sudbury Transit's service area to one larger than most Ontario municipal and regional public transit agencies. The Downtown Transit Centre is the primary hub for local transit in Sudbury.\n\n====Air====\n\n[[File:Greater Sudbury Airport (5707786702).jpg|thumb|[[Sudbury Airport]] is an [[airport]] that serves Greater Sudbury, handling scheduled flights throughout Ontario.]]\n\nThe [[Sudbury Airport|Greater Sudbury Airport]] maintains two paved runways {{convert|6600|ft|abbr=on|}} and {{convert|5000|ft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{CFS}}</ref> in length and serves 270,784 passengers per year (2017).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flysudbury.ca/flysudbury/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=91%3Afacts-and-demographics&catid=35%3Abusiness-gsa&Itemid=53&lang=en |title=Facts and Demographics |publisher=Greater Sudbury Airport |accessdate=August 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115113749/http://www.flysudbury.ca/flysudbury/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=91%3Afacts-and-demographics&catid=35%3Abusiness-gsa&Itemid=53&lang=en |archive-date=November 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The airport is served by three regional carrier lines: [[Air Canada Express]] to [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]], [[Porter Airlines]] to [[Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport]] and [[Bearskin Airlines]] to several destinations in Northern Ontario including [[North Bay/Jack Garland Airport|North Bay]], [[Sault Ste. Marie Airport|Sault Ste. Marie]], [[Timmins Victor M. Power Airport|Timmins]] and [[Thunder Bay International Airport|Thunder Bay]].\n\n====Intercity transportation====\n\nSeveral different agencies provide intercity transportation to Sudbury. [[Via Rail]]'s [[Sudbury\u2013White River train]] (a remnant of the old ''Lake Superior'' passenger service to [[Thunder Bay]]) serves a number of remote interior communities, some of which are not accessible by road, from the downtown [[Sudbury station (Ontario)|Sudbury station]]. To the north and east of the city, [[Capreol station]] and [[Sudbury Junction station]] are stops on Via Rail's transcontinental passenger service, the ''[[Canadian (train)|Canadian]]'', which passes through the area twice a week in each direction.\n\nIntercity motor coach service is available at the [[Sudbury Ontario Northland Bus Terminal]], which is a stop for [[Ontario Northland Transportation Commission|Ontario Northland]] and [[Greyhound Canada]] motor coaches. Destinations include North Bay, [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]], [[Hearst, Ontario|Hearst]], [[Barrie]], [[Toronto]], and [[Ottawa]].\n\n====Roads and highways====\n\n{{See also|List of numbered roads in Greater Sudbury}}\n\nGreater Sudbury is the only census division in Northern Ontario that maintains a system of numbered [[List of numbered roads in Greater Sudbury|municipal roads]], similar to the [[County highway#Canada|county road]] system in the southern part of the province. There are three highways connecting Sudbury to the rest of Ontario: [[Ontario Highway 17|Highway 17]] is the main branch of the [[Trans-Canada Highway]], connecting the city to points east and west. An approximately {{convert|21|km|abbr=on}} segment of Highway 17, from Mikkola to Whitefish, is [[Controlled-access highway|freeway]]. The highway bypasses the city via two separately-constructed roads, the [[Southwest and Southeast Bypasses]], that form a partial [[ring road]] around the southern end of the city's urban core for traffic travelling through Highway 17. The former alignment of Highway 17 through the city is now [[Sudbury Municipal Road 55|Municipal Road 55]]. [[Ontario Highway 69|Highway 69]], also a branch of the Trans-Canada Highway, leads south to [[Parry Sound, Ontario|Parry Sound]], where it connects to the [[Ontario Highway 400|Highway 400]] freeway to Toronto; Highway 400 is being extended to Greater Sudbury and is scheduled for completion in the 2020s.<ref name=delayed>[http://www.thesudburystar.com/2015/03/06/highway-69-to-be-delayed-province-admits \"Highway 69 to be delayed, province admits\"]. ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', March 7, 2015.</ref> [[Ontario Highway 144|Highway 144]] leads north to [[Ontario Highway 101|Highway 101]] in [[Timmins]].\n\n==Media==\n{{Main|Media in Greater Sudbury}}\nAs the largest city in Northern Ontario, Greater Sudbury is the region's primary media centre. Due to the relatively small size of the region's individual media markets, most of the region is served at least partially by Sudbury-based media. [[CICI-TV]] produces almost all local programming on the [[CTV Northern Ontario]] system, and the CBC Radio stations [[CBCS-FM]] and [[CBON-FM]] broadcast to the entire region through extensive [[Broadcast relay station|rebroadcaster]] networks. As well, most of the commercial radio stations in Northeastern Ontario's smaller cities simulcast programming produced in Sudbury for at least a portion of their programming schedules, particularly in weekend and evening slots.\n\nSudbury has two local newspapers: the ''[[Sudbury Star]]'', owned by [[Postmedia Network|Postmedia]], is published six days a week and has a weekday circulation of 17,530 as of 2006;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/advertising/2006/EffectiveRecruitment.pdf |title=Advertising Rates & Specs |publisher=Northern Star |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518184946/http://www.northernlife.ca/advertising/2006/EffectiveRecruitment.pdf |archivedate=May 18, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and ''Northern Life'', which publishes twice a week and has a weekday circulation of 45,761 as of 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/advertising/2009/Sept2009Audit.pdf |title=Community Newspaper Circulation Statement |publisher=Northern Star |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111201140718/http://www.northernlife.ca/advertising/2009/Sept2009Audit.pdf |archivedate=December 1, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ''Northern Life'' uses the name sudbury.com on its web edition, but is still bannered as ''Northern Life'' in print. There is also one monthly print publication, ''South Side Story'', and a weekly francophone publication, ''[[Le Voyageur]]''. [[Laurentian Media Group|Laurentian Publishing]], the publishers of ''Northern Life'', also publish a number of regional interest magazines, including ''Northern Ontario Business'' and the quarterly ''Sudbury Living''.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Greater Sudbury}}\nNotable people from Sudbury include television game-show ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' host [[Alex Trebek]], [[Power Corporation of Canada]] chairman [[Paul Desmarais Jr.]], mining speculator and philanthropist [[Frank Giustra]], president of [[United Steelworkers]], [[Leo Gerard]], former [[Anaheim Ducks]] and [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] head coach [[Randy Carlyle]], [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] general manager, [[Michiel Zegers]] [[Farhan Zaidi]], and Olympian [[Alex Baumann]] who won two gold medals and set two world records in swimming. [[Rebecca Johnston]] who plays for the [[Canada women's national ice hockey team|Canadian Women's Hockey Team]], and [[Tessa Bonhomme]] was a former player. Sudbury has produced 81 [[National Hockey League]] hockey players, a number larger than any European city, including [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] inductees [[Eddie Giacomin]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Art Ross]], and [[Al Arbour]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hockey-reference.com/friv/birthplaces.cgi?country=CA&province=ON&state= |title=NHL Players Born in Ontario, Canada |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher=Hockey-Reference.com |accessdate=15 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Greater Sudbury]]\n* [[List of francophone communities in Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Oiva W. Saarinen. ''From Meteorite Impact to Constellation City: A Historical Geography of Greater Sudbury'' (2013)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Greater Sudbury, Ontario}}\n*[http://www.greatersudbury.ca/ City of Greater Sudbury]\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre = Greater Sudbury<br />{{nobold|(surrounds [[Wahnapitae First Nation|Wahnapitae 11]])}}\n | North = [[Unorganized North Sudbury District|Unorganized North Sudbury]]\n | Northeast =\n | East = [[Markstay-Warren]]\n | Southeast =\n | South = [[Whitefish Lake 6, Ontario|Whitefish Lake 6]], [[Unorganized North Sudbury District|Unorganized North Sudbury]]\n | Southwest = [[Unorganized North Sudbury District|Unorganized North Sudbury]]<br />[[Killarney, Ontario|Killarney]]\n | West = [[Nairn and Hyman]]\n | Northwest =\n | image =\n}}\n{{Greater Sudbury}}\n{{Subdivisions of Ontario}}\n{{Census metropolitan areas by size}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Greater Sudbury| ]]\n[[Category:Hudson's Bay Company trading posts]]\n[[Category:Mining communities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Single-tier municipalities in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|City in Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Greater Sudbury\n|native_name = {{lang|fr|Grand-Sudbury}}\n| official_name         = City of Greater Sudbury<br /><small>''Ville du Grand Sudbury''</small>\n|settlement_type        = [[List of cities in Ontario|City]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Single-tier municipalities|single-tier]])\n|nicknames               = [[List of city nicknames and slogans in Canada#Ontario|\"Nickel Capital\", \"Nickel City\", \"The Big Nickel\" \"City of Lakes\", \"Sudz\"(colloquially)]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/2013/11/17/ukrainians-say-goodbye-to-nickel-city | title=Ukrainians say goodbye to Nickel City | author=Harold Carmichael | newspaper=[[Sudbury Star]] | publisher=[[Canoe Sun Media]] | date=November 18, 2013 | accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Restoring the City of Lakes' aquatic luster|author= Sudbury Northern Life Staff|url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2010/03/freshwater-ecology160310.aspx |newspaper= [[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]|date= March 16, 2010|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n|motto                  = ''Aedificemus''<br /><small>([[Latin]] for \"Come, let us build together\"</small>)\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          = From top left: Downtown Sudbury Skyline, Big Nickel, Bridge of Nations, Inco Superstack, Bell Park, and Science North\n|image_flag             = Flag of Sudbury Ontario.svg\n|flag_size              =\n|image_blank_emblem     = Greater Sudbury logo.svg\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_shield           = Gtsudburycoa.png\n|shield_size            =\n|image_map              = Map of Ontario GREATER SUDBURY.svg\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|pushpin_map            = Canada\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location of Greater Sudbury in Canada\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = Canada\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Ontario]]\n|subdivision_type2      =\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      =\n|subdivision_type4      =\n|subdivision_name4      =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           = [[List of mayors of Greater Sudbury|Mayor]]\n|leader_name            = [[Brian Bigger]]\n|leader_title2          = Governing Body\n|leader_name2           = [[Greater Sudbury City Council]]\n|leader_title3          =[[House of Commons of Canada|MPs]]\n|leader_name3           =[[Paul Lefebvre]]&nbsp;([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])<br />[[Marc Serr\u00e9]]&nbsp;([[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]])\n|leader_title4          =[[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|MPPs]]\n|leader_name4           =[[France G\u00e9linas]]&nbsp;([[Ontario New Democratic Party|NDP]])<br />[[Jamie West]]&nbsp;([[Ontario New Democratic Party|NDP]])\n|established_title      = Founded\n|established_date       = 1883\n|established_title2     = Incorporated (Town)\n|established_date2      = 1893 (as Sudbury)\n|established_title3     = Re-Incorporated (City)\n|established_date3      = 1930 (as Sudbury) \n|established_title4     = &nbsp;\n|established_date4      = 2001 (as Greater Sudbury)\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref              =<!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes         =<ref name=\"Census\"/>\n|area_total_km2         = 3228.35\n|area_land_km2          =\n|area_water_km2         =\n|area_water_percent     =\n|area_urban_km2         = 75.93\n|area_metro_km2         = 3924.48\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_footnotes   =<ref name=\"Census\"/>\n|population_note        =\n|population_total       = {{#statements:P1082|from=Q383434}} ([[List of the 100 largest municipalities in Canada by population|29th]])\n|population_density_km2 = 49.7\n|population_metro       = 164689 ([[List of metropolitan areas in Canada|24th]])\n|population_density_metro_km2 = 49.5\n|population_urban       = 88054<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0904&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&SearchText=Sudbury&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=0904&TABID=1&type=0 |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Sudbury [Population centre], Ontario and Ontario [Province]|publisher = [[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|population_density_urban_km2 = 1159.7\n|timezone               = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = \u221205:00\n|timezone_DST           = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST         = \u221204:00\n|coordinates            = {{coord|46|29|24|N|81|00|36|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 347.5\n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of P postal codes of Canada|P3A to P3G, P3L, P3N, P3P, P3Y]]\n|area_code              =[[Area codes 705 and 249|705/249]]\n|blank_name             = Telephone exchanges\n|blank_info             = ''705''\u2013207, 222, 280, 396, 397, 479, 507, 521, 522, 523, 524, 525, 546, 547, 550, 551, 552, 553, 554, 556, 560, 561, 562, 564, 566, 585, 596, 618, 626, 662, 664, 665, 669, 670, 671, 673, 674, 675, 677, 682, 688, 690, 691, 692, 693, 694, 695, 698, 699, 805, 822, 853, 855, 858, 866, 867, 897, 898, 899, 919, 920, 929, 966, 967, 969, 983\n''249''-810, 878\n|blank2_name             = [[List of highways in Ontario|Highways]]\n|blank2_info             = {{jct|state=ON|Hwy|17|TCH}}<br />{{nowrap|{{jct|state=ON|Hwy|400|TCH}}}}<br />{{jct|state=ON|Hwy|144}}\n|website                = [http://www.greatersudbury.ca/ www.greatersudbury.ca]\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Sudbury''', officially '''Greater Sudbury''' ({{lang-fr|Grand-Sudbury}}), is a city in [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the largest city in [[Northern Ontario]] by population, with a population of 161,531 at the [[2016 Canadian Census]].<ref name=\"Census\">{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=302&SR=176&S=86&O=A&RPP=25&PR=35&CMA=0&CSD=0 |title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories, and census subdivisions (municipalities), 2016 and 2011 censuses \u2013 100% data|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=February 6, 2017 |work= |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> By land area, it is the largest in Ontario and the [[List of the 100 largest cities and towns in Canada by area|fifth largest in Canada]]. It is administratively a [[Unitary authority#Canadasingle-tier municipality|Unitary authority]], and thus not part of any district, county, or [[regional municipality]].\n\nThe Sudbury region was inhabited by the [[Ojibwe]] people of the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin group]] for thousands of years prior to the founding of Sudbury following the discovery of [[nickel]] ore in 1883 during the construction of the transcontinental railway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greatersudbury.ca/live/about-greater-sudbury/history/ |title=History - Greater Sudbury |publisher=Greatersudbury.ca |date=2001-01-01 |accessdate=2017-07-26}}</ref> Greater Sudbury was formed in 2001 by merging the cities and towns of the former [[Regional Municipality of Sudbury]] with several previously unincorporated townships. Being located inland, the local climate is extremely seasonal with average January lows of around {{convert|-18|C|0}} and average July highs of {{convert|25|C|0}}.<ref name=\"EnvironmentCanada\" />\n\nThe population resides in an urban core and many smaller communities scattered around 330 lakes and among hills of rock blackened by historical [[smelting]] activity. Sudbury was once a major lumber centre and a world leader in nickel mining. Mining and related industries dominated the economy for much of the 20th century. The two major mining companies which shaped the history of Sudbury were Inco, now [[Vale Limited]], which employed more than 25% of the population by the 1970s, and [[Falconbridge Ltd.|Falconbridge]], now [[Glencore]]. Sudbury has since expanded from its resource-based economy to emerge as the major retail, economic, health and educational centre for Northeastern Ontario. Sudbury is also home to a large [[Franco-Ontarian]] population that influences its arts and culture.\n\n==History==\n<!-- {{Main|History of Sudbury, Ontario}} -->\nThe Sudbury region was inhabited by the [[Ojibwe]] people of the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin group]] as early as 9,000 years ago following the retreat of the last continental ice sheet.<ref name=\"canadianencyclopedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1SEC867615 |title=Sudbury |last=Saarinen |first=O.W. |date=21 October 2012 |publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |access-date=February 3, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211124832/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1SEC867615 |archivedate=December 11, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 1850, a large tract of land, including what is now Sudbury, was signed over to the [[The Crown|British Crown]] by local Ojibwe chiefs as a part of the [[Robinson Treaty#Robinson Huron Treaty|Robinson Huron Treaty]]. In exchange the Crown pledged to pay an annuity to [[First Nations]] people, which was originally set at $1.60 per treaty member and increased incrementally; its last increase was in 1874, leaving it fixed at $4.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manitoulin.ca/judge-rules-robinson-huron-treatys-4-annuity-needs-update/ |title=Judge rules Robinson Huron Treaty\u2019s $4 annuity needs update |first=Michael |last=Erskine |date=9 January 2019 |access-date=10 August 2019 |newspaper=The Manitoulin Expositor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thesudburystar.com/news/local-news/first-nation-in-northern-ontario-win-historic-lawsuit |title=First Nations in Northern Ontario win historic lawsuit |first=Harold |last=Carmichael |newspaper=[[The Sudbury Star]] |date=25 December 2018 |access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrench [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] were the first to establish a European settlement when they set up a [[mission (station)|mission]] called Sainte-Anne-des-Pins, just before the construction of the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] in 1883. The Sainte-Anne-des-Pins church played a prominent role in the development of Franco-Ontarian culture in the region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Sudbury03.html |title=Sainte-Anne des Pines |publisher=Ontario's Historical Plaques}}</ref>\n[[File:Sudbury 1888.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] junction in Sudbury in 1888. Construction for the railway led to the discovery of high concentrations of [[nickel]]-[[copper]] [[ore]] at the edge of the [[Sudbury Basin]].]]\nDuring construction of the railway in 1883, blasting and excavation revealed high concentrations of [[nickel]]-[[copper]] [[ore]] at [[Murray Mine]] on the edge of the [[Sudbury Basin]]. This discovery brought the first waves of European settlers, who arrived not only to work at the mines, but also to build a service station for railway workers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.investsudbury.ca/index.php?lang=en&Itemid=222 |title=History |date=2013 |publisher=Greater Sudbury Development Corporation |access-date=February 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208160218/http://www.investsudbury.ca/index.php?lang=en&Itemid=222 |archive-date=February 8, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nJames Worthington, the superintendent of construction on the Northern Ontario segment of the railway, selected the name Sudbury after [[Sudbury, Suffolk]], in England, which was the hometown of his wife Caroline Hitchcock.<ref name=\"canadianencyclopedia\" /><ref>Thomas, Ray and Pearsall, Kathy (1994). ''Sudbury''. Boston Mills Press. {{ISBN|978-1-55046-110-7}}.</ref> Sudbury was incorporated as a town in 1893,<ref>{{cite news |title=History retold through archives |author=Darren MacDonald |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2012/05/04-archive-opening-sudbury.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]] |date= May 3, 2012|access-date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> and its first mayor was Joseph \u00c9tienne aka [[Stephen Fournier]].<ref name = railtown>Wallace, C. M.; & Thomson, Ashley (Eds.) (1993). ''Sudbury: Rail Town to Regional Capital'' (3rd ed.). [[Dundurn Press]]. {{ISBN|978-1-55002-170-7}}.</ref>\n\nThe American inventor [[Thomas Edison]] visited the Sudbury area as a prospector in 1901. He is credited with the original discovery of the ore body at [[Nickel Centre#Falconbridge|Falconbridge]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sudburymuseums.ca/index.cfm?app=w_vmuseum&lang=en&currID=2031&parID=2029 |title=Thomas Edison |website= Greater Sudbury Heritage Museums |publisher=City of Greater Sudbury |access-date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> Rich deposits of [[Millerite|nickel sulphide]] ore were discovered in the [[Sudbury Basin]] geological formation. The construction of the railway allowed exploitation of these mineral resources and shipment of the commodities to markets and ports, as well as large-scale lumber extraction.<ref name=railtown />\n\nMining began to replace lumber as the primary industry as the area's transportation network was improved to include trams. These enabled workers to live in one community and work in another.<ref name=railtown /> Sudbury's economy was dominated by the mining industry for much of the 20th century. Two major mining companies were created: [[Vale Limited|Inco]] in 1902 and [[Falconbridge Ltd.|Falconbridge]] in 1928. They became two of the city's major employers and two of the world's leading producers of nickel.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n[[File:Bird's Eye View of the Smelting Works of the Canadian Copper Co, Ontario (HS85-10-27230).jpg|thumb|left|Smelting works of the Canadian Copper Company prior to [[World War I]]. Most of the nickel mined from Sudbury was used in the manufacturing of artillery during the war.]]\n\nThrough the decades that followed, Sudbury's economy went through boom and bust cycles as world demand for nickel fluctuated. Demand was high during the [[World War I|First World War]], when Sudbury-mined nickel was used extensively in the manufacturing of artillery in [[Sheffield]], England. It bottomed out when the war ended and then rose again in the mid-1920s as peacetime uses for nickel began to develop. The town was reincorporated as a city in 1930.\n\nThe city recovered from the [[Great Depression in Canada|Great Depression]] much more quickly than almost any other city in North America due to increased demand for nickel in the 1930s. Sudbury was the fastest-growing city and one of the wealthiest cities in Canada for most of the decade. Many of the city's social problems in the Great Depression era were not caused by unemployment or poverty, but due to the difficulty in keeping up with all of the new infrastructure demands created by rapid growth \u2014 for example, employed mineworkers sometimes ended up living in [[boarding house]]s or makeshift [[shanty town]]s, because demand for new housing was rising faster than supply.<ref name=railtown /> Between 1936 and 1941, the city was ordered into [[receivership]] by the [[Ontario Municipal Board]].<ref name=railtown /> Another economic slowdown affected the city in 1937, but the city's fortunes rose again with wartime demands during the [[World War II|Second World War]]. The [[Frood Mine]] alone accounted for 40 percent of all the nickel used in [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[artillery]] production during the war. After the end of the war, Sudbury was in a good position to supply nickel to the United States government when it decided to stockpile non-[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] supplies during the [[Cold War]].<ref name=railtown />\n[[File:Banner in Sudbury, Ontario, circa 1942.jpg|thumb|left|Banner welcoming [[Underground mining (hard rock)|hard rock]] miners into Sudbury. Nickel mines became vital to the war effort, with [[Frood Mine]] accounting for 40 percent of all nickel used in [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] artillery production.]]\nThe open coke beds used in the early to mid 20th century and logging for fuel resulted in a near-total loss of native vegetation in the area. Consequently, the terrain was made up of exposed rocky outcrops permanently stained charcoal black by the air pollution from the roasting yards. [[Acid rain]] added more staining, in a layer that penetrates up to {{convert|3|in|abbr=on}} into the once pink-grey [[granite]].\n\nThe construction of the [[Inco Superstack]] in 1972 dispersed sulphuric acid through the air over a much wider area, reducing the acidity of local precipitation. This enabled the city to begin an environmental recovery program. In the late 1970s, private and public interests combined to establish a \"regreening\" effort. [[Calcium oxide|Lime]] was spread over the charred soil by hand and by aircraft. Seeds of wild [[Poaceae|grasses]] and other vegetation were also spread. As of 2010, 9.2&nbsp;million new trees have been planted in the city.<ref>[http://www.greatersudbury.ca/content/div_landreclamation/documents/2010%20Final%20Annual%20Report.pdf Annual Report 2010], City of Greater Sudbury Land Reclamation Program.</ref><!--needs page number--> [[Vale Limited|Vale]] has begun to rehabilitate the [[Spoil tip|slag heap]]s that surrounds their smelter in the Copper Cliff area with the planting of grass and trees,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greatersudbury.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_earthcare&lang=en&currID=6855 |title=Vale Community-based Initiatives |publisher=The City of Greater Sudbury |accessdate=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811013206/http://www.greatersudbury.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_earthcare&lang=en&currID=6855 |archive-date=August 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as the use of [[biosolids]] to stabilize and regreen [[tailings]] areas.<ref>[https://www.northernontariobusiness.com/regional-news/sudbury/biosolids-rejuvenate-mining-wasteland-983489 \"Biosolids rejuvenate mining wasteland\"]. ''[[Northern Ontario Business]]'', July 13, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 1978, the workers of Sudbury's largest mining corporation, Inco (now Vale), [[1978 INCO strike|embarked on a strike]] over production and employment cutbacks. The strike, which lasted for nine months, badly damaged Sudbury's economy. The city government was spurred to launch a project to diversify the city's economy. Through an aggressive strategy, the city tried to attract new employers and industries through the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=railtown />\n[[File:Sudbury smokestack 1976.jpg|thumb|The [[Inco Superstack]] in 1976, four years after its completion. It was built to disperse sulphuric acid, and reduce the acidity of local precipitation.]]\nThe city of Sudbury and its suburban communities, which were reorganized into the [[Regional Municipality of Sudbury]] in 1973, was subsequently merged in 2001 into the single-tier city of Greater Sudbury. In 2006, both of the city's major mining companies, Canadian-based Inco and Falconbridge, were taken over by new owners: Inco was acquired by the Brazilian company CVRD (now renamed [[Vale (company)|Vale]]), while Falconbridge was purchased by the Swiss company [[Xstrata]], which itself was purchased by Anglo\u2013Swiss Glencore, forming [[Glencore|Glencore Xstrata]]. Xstrata donated the historic [[Edison Building (Falconbridge)|Edison Building]], the onetime head office of Falconbridge, to the city in 2007 to serve as the new home of the municipal archives.<ref>[http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/pubapps/newsreleases/index.cfm?Release_id=1877&lang=en \"Xstrata Nickel donates building to City of Greater Sudbury for community archives\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928035745/http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/pubapps/newsreleases/index.cfm?Release_id=1877&lang=en |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref> On September 19, 2008, a fire destroyed the historic [[Sudbury Steelworkers Hall]] on Frood Road.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steelworkers Hall goes up in flames |author=Laurel Myers and Heidi Ulrichsen|url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/policeandCourt/2008/091908-fireTOP.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]|date=Sep 19, 2008 |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref> A strike at Vale's operations, which began on July 13, 2009, was tentatively resolved in July 2010.<ref>[https://montrealgazette.com/business/Vale+reaches+deal+with+workers+Sudbury+nickel+mine/3237157/story.html \"Vale reaches deal with workers at Sudbury nickel mine\"]{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]'', July 5, 2010.</ref> The 2009 strike lasted longer than the devastating 1978 strike, but had a much more modest effect on the city's economy than the earlier action\u2014unlike in 1978, the local rate of [[unemployment]] ''declined'' slightly during the 2009 strike.<ref>Adam Radwanski, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/adam-radwanski/why-sudbury-is-an-unlikely-magnet-for-global-education/article1680784/ \"Why Sudbury is an unlikely magnet for global education\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', August 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nThe ecology of the Sudbury region has recovered dramatically, helped by regreening programs and improved mining practices. The [[United Nations]] honoured twelve cities in the world, including Sudbury, with the Local Government Honours Award at the 1992 [[Earth Summit]] to recognise the city's community-based environmental reclamation strategies. By 2010, the regreening programs had successfully rehabilitated {{convert|3,350|ha|abbr=on}} of land in the city; however, approximately {{convert|30,000|ha|abbr=on}} of land have yet to be rehabilitated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Regreening: 3,350 hectares done, but 30,000 hectares to go|author= Bill Bradley |url=http://www.northernlife.ca/news/localNews/2010/01/regreening260110.aspx |newspaper=[[Northern Life (newspaper)|Northern Life]]|date= Jan 25, 2010|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n{{See also|List of lakes in Greater Sudbury}}\nSudbury has 330 lakes over {{convert|10|ha|abbr=on}} within the city limits.<ref name=\"grandsudbury.ca\">{{cite web |url=http://www.grandsudbury.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_lakewaterquality&lang=en&currID=688 |title=City of Lakes |author= City of Sudbury |year=2013|publisher= City of Sudbury |accessdate=12 August 2013}}</ref> The most prominent is [[Lake Wanapitei]], the largest lake in the world completely contained within the boundaries of a single city. [[Ramsey Lake]], a few kilometres south of downtown Sudbury, held the same record before the municipal amalgamation in 2001 brought Lake Wanapitei fully inside the city limits.<ref name=\"grandsudbury.ca\"/> Sudbury is divided into two main watersheds: to the east is the [[French River (Ontario)|French River]] watershed which flows into [[Georgian Bay]] and to the west is the [[Spanish River (Ontario)|Spanish River]] watershed which flows into [[Lake Huron]].<ref name=\"grandsudbury.ca\"/>\n[[File:Wanapitei River.JPG|thumb|left|[[Wanapitei River]] in Sudbury. Located in the [[Great Lakes Basin]], it is a tributary of the [[French River (Ontario)|French River]].]]\nSudbury is built around many small, rocky mountains with exposed [[igneous rock]] of the [[Canadian Shield|Canadian (Precambrian) Shield]]. The ore deposits in Sudbury are part of a large geological structure known as the [[Sudbury Basin]], which are the remnants of a nearly two billion-year-old [[impact crater]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Mountain of a meteor hit ancient Sudbury|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=7ef9efbc-7937-4102-a6a1-21245c546ea5|publisher=The Ottawa Citizen|date=30 August 2007|accessdate=8 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140321062745/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=7ef9efbc-7937-4102-a6a1-21245c546ea5|archivedate=March 21, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> long thought to be the result of a [[meteorite]] collision, more recent analysis has suggested that the crater may in fact have been created by a [[comet]].<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/18/sudbury-basin-comet-impact-crater_n_6168408.html \"Canada's Vast 'Sudbury Basin' Was Created By Comet, Study Says\"]. ''[[Huffington Post]]'', November 18, 2014.</ref>\n\nSudbury's [[pentlandite]], [[pyrite]] and [[pyrrhotite]] ores contain profitable amounts of many elements\u2014primarily nickel and copper, but also platinum, palladium and other valuable metals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ontario.ca/en/about_ontario/004467.html|title=About Ontario|website=Ontario.ca|accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nLocal smelting of the ore releases this sulphur into the atmosphere where it combines with water vapour to form [[Sulfuric acid|sulphuric acid]], contributing to [[acid rain]]. As a result, Sudbury has had a widespread reputation as a wasteland.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/TECH/9609/12/greening.sudbury/ | work=CNN | title=Canadian wasteland gets green makeover}}</ref> In parts of the city, vegetation was devastated by acid rain and logging to provide fuel for early [[smelting]] techniques. To a lesser extent, the area's ecology was also impacted by lumber camps in the area providing wood for the reconstruction of Chicago after the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of 1871. While other logging areas in Northeastern Ontario were also involved in that effort, the emergence of mining related processes in the following decade made it significantly harder for new trees to grow to full maturity in the Sudbury area than elsewhere.<ref name=railtown />\n[[File:Blackened rocks in Sudbury, Ontario.JPG|thumb|Erosion has resulted in [[bedrock]] being exposed in many parts of the city, many of which were charred to a pitted, dark black appearance.]]\nThe resulting erosion exposed [[bedrock]] in many parts of the city, which was charred in most places to a pitted, dark black appearance. There was not a complete lack of vegetation in the region as [[Betula papyrifera|paper birch]] and wild [[blueberry]] patches thrived in the acidic soils. During the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] manned lunar exploration program, [[NASA]] astronauts trained in Sudbury to become familiar with impact [[breccia]] and [[shatter cone]]s, rare rock formations produced by large meteorite impacts. However, the popular misconception that they were visiting Sudbury because it purportedly resembled the lifeless surface of the [[Moon]] persists.<ref>[http://castroller.com/podcasts/TheCurrent/1325020 \"A Mining Town\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708123819/http://castroller.com/podcasts/TheCurrent/1325020 |date=July 8, 2011 }}. ''[[The Current (radio show)|The Current]]'', November 16, 2009.</ref>\n\nThe city's [[Nickel District Conservation Authority]] operates a [[Protected area|conservation area]], the [[Lake Laurentian Conservation Area]], in the city's south end. Other unique environmental projects in the city include the Fielding Bird Sanctuary, a protected area along [[Ontario Highway 17|Highway 17]] near [[Walden, Ontario#Lively|Lively]] that provides a managed natural habitat for birds, and a hiking and nature trail near [[Nickel Centre#Coniston|Coniston]], which is named in honour of scientist [[Jane Goodall]].<ref name=\"sudbury\">{{cite web|url=http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_landreclamation&lang=en&currID=1036|archive-url=https://archive.is/20110728060209/http://www.city.greatersudbury.on.ca/cms/index.cfm?app=div_landreclamation&lang=en&currID=1036|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 28, 2011|title=City of Greater Sudbury|date=July 28, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSix [[List of protected areas of Ontario|provincial park]]s ([[Chiniguchi Waterway Provincial Park|Chiniguchi River]], [[Daisy Lake Uplands Provincial Park|Daisy Lake Uplands]], [[Fairbank Provincial Park|Fairbank]], [[Killarney Lakelands and Headwaters Provincial Park|Killarney Lakelands and Headwaters]], [[Lake Wanapitei|Wanapitei]] and [[Windy Lake Provincial Park|Windy Lake]]) and two provincial conservation reserves (MacLennan Esker Forest and Tilton Forest) are also located partially or entirely within the city boundaries.\n\n===Climate===\n\nGreater Sudbury has a [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: ''Dfb''). This region has warm and often hot, humid summers with long, cold and snowy winters. It is situated north of the [[Great Lakes]], making it prone to arctic air masses. Monthly precipitation is equal year round, with snow cover expected six months of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_e.html?stnID=4132&prov=&lang=e&dCode=1&dispBack=1&StationName=sudbury&SearchType=Contains&province=ALL&provBut=&month1=0&month2=12|title=Canadian Climate Normals 1971-2000 Station Data - Climate - Environment and Climate Change Canada|first=Environment and Climate Change|last=Canada|website=climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca}}</ref> Although extreme weather events are rare, [[Sudbury tornado|one of the worst tornadoes]] in Canadian history struck the city and its suburbs on August 20, 1970, killing six people, injuring two hundred, and causing more than [[Canadian dollar|C$]]17 million in damages.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/environment/extreme-weather/extreme-weather-general/freak-tornado-kills-six-in-sudbury.html | work=[[CBC News]] | title=CBC Digital Archives|accessdate= August 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe highest temperature ever recorded in Greater Sudbury was {{convert|41.1|C}} on July 13, 1936.<ref name=\"July 1936\"/> The lowest temperature ever recorded was {{convert|-48.3|C}} on December 29, 1933.<ref name=\"December 1933\"/>\n\n{{Weather box\n| collapsed = yes\n|location = [[Sudbury Airport]], 1981\u22122010 normals, extremes 1887\u2212present{{efn|Extreme high and low temperatures in the table are from Sudbury (June 1887 to July 1930), [[Nickel Centre|Coniston]] (August 1930 to September 1947), Sudbury (October 1947 to January 1954), and [[Sudbury Airport]] (February 1954 to present).}}\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan maximum humidex = 7.1\n|Feb maximum humidex = 10.0\n|Mar maximum humidex = 28.0\n|Apr maximum humidex = 30.7\n|May maximum humidex = 39.4\n|Jun maximum humidex = 41.4\n|Jul maximum humidex = 42.9\n|Aug maximum humidex = 49.2\n|Sep maximum humidex = 38.7\n|Oct maximum humidex = 34.3\n|Nov maximum humidex = 20.0\n|Dec maximum humidex = 17.7\n|year maximum humidex = 49.2\n|Jan record high C = 10.0\n|Feb record high C = 9.4\n|Mar record high C = 25.9\n|Apr record high C = 29.8\n|May record high C = 35.6\n|Jun record high C = 35.7\n|Jul record high C = 41.1\n|Aug record high C = 36.7\n|Sep record high C = 34.4\n|Oct record high C = 27.8\n|Nov record high C = 20.0\n|Dec record high C = 15.6\n|year record high C = 41.1\n|Jan high C = -8.0\n|Feb high C = -5.5\n|Mar high C = 0.4\n|Apr high C = 9.2\n|May high C = 17.0\n|Jun high C = 22.2\n|Jul high C = 24.8\n|Aug high C = 23.4\n|Sep high C = 18.1\n|Oct high C = 10.3\n|Nov high C = 2.6\n|Dec high C = -4.4\n|year high C = 9.2\n|Jan mean C = -13.0\n|Feb mean C = -10.8\n|Mar mean C = -4.9\n|Apr mean C = 3.8\n|May mean C = 11.1\n|Jun mean C = 16.5\n|Jul mean C = 19.1\n|Aug mean C = 18.0\n|Sep mean C = 13.0\n|Oct mean C = 6.0\n|Nov mean C = -1.0\n|Dec mean C = -8.6\n|year mean C = 4.1\n|Jan low C = -17.9\n|Feb low C = -16.0\n|Mar low C = -10.2\n|Apr low C = -1.7\n|May low C = 5.2\n|Jun low C = 10.7\n|Jul low C = 13.4\n|Aug low C = 12.4\n|Sep low C = 7.8\n|Oct low C = 1.7\n|Nov low C = -4.7\n|Dec low C = -12.7\n|year low C = -1.0\n|Jan record lo