ic bishops]]\n[[Category:Irish Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Cathedral Basilica of Saints Peter and Paul, Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "86.27.84.141", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Conwell"}
{"title_page": "Eric Foner", "text_new": "{{short description|American historian}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Eric Foner\n| image              = Eric Foner, New York City, New York, September 15, 2009.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| alt                = A grey-haired bespectacled man wearing a light blue shirt and sitting on a chair behind a desk; behind him is a bookshelf and a wall mounted with certificates and awards\n| caption            = Foner at his [[New York City]] office in 2009\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age |mf=yes|1943|2|7}}\n| birth_place        = {{nowrap|[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], US}}\n| alma_mater         = {{ubl | [[Columbia University]] | [[Oriel College, Oxford]]}}\n| awards             = {{ubl | [[Bancroft Prize]] (1989; 2011) | [[Lincoln Prize]] (2011) | [[Pulitzer Prize]] (2011)}}\n| parents            = {{hlist | [[Jack D. Foner]] | Liza Kraitz}}\n| spouse             = {{ubl | {{marriage|[[Naomi Foner Gyllenhaal|Naomi Achs]]|1965|1977|reason=divorced}} | {{marriage|[[Lynn Garafola]]|1980}}}}\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = [[Richard Hofstadter]]\n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = History\n| sub_discipline     = [[History of the United States|American]] [[political history]]\n| workplaces         = {{ubl | [[City College of New York]] | [[Columbia University]]}}\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Elizabeth Hinton]]\n* [[Mae Ngai]]\n}}\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = ''[[The Fiery Trial]]'' (2010)\n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n}}\n\n'''Eric Foner''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|o\u028a|n|\u0259r}}; born February 7, 1943) is an American [[historian]]. He writes extensively on [[History of the United States|American]] [[political history]], the history of freedom, the early [[History of the United States Republican Party|history of the Republican Party]], [[African-American]] biography, [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]], and [[historiography]], and has been a member of the faculty at the [[Columbia University]] Department of History since 1982. He is the author of several popular textbooks. According to the Open Syllabus Project, Foner is the most frequently cited author on college syllabi for history courses.<ref>https://opensyllabus.org/results-list/authors?size=50&fields=History</ref>\n\nFoner is a leading contemporary historian of the  Reconstruction period, having published ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877'' in 1989 and more than 10 other books on the topic.<ref name=\"reconstruction73\">Perman, Michael. \"Eric Foner's Reconstruction: A Finished Revolution\". ''Reviews in American History,'' Vol. 17, No. 1. (Mar., 1989), pp. 73\u201378.</ref> His online courses on \"The Civil War and Reconstruction\", published in 2014, are available from Columbia University on ColumbiaX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edx.org/xseries/civil-war-reconstruction|title=The Civil War and Reconstruction|date=2015-01-07|website=edX|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Foner's ''[[The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery]]'' (2010) won the [[Pulitzer Prize for History]], the [[Lincoln Prize]], and the [[Bancroft Prize]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/house-divided/2011/02/prestigious_lincoln_prize_goes.html |work=The Washington Post |title=Prestigious Lincoln Prize goes to Eric Foner}}</ref><ref>http://newswire.ascribe.org/cgi-bin/behold.pl?ascribeid=20110210.071303&time=02%2000%20PST&year=2011&public=0{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/historian-foner-among-3-winners-of-bancroft-prize-news-hollywood-ld2dkndehfi.html |title=Historian Foner among 3 winners of Bancroft Prize |publisher=Sify.com |date=2011-03-28 |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref> Foner previously won the Bancroft in 1989 for his book ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877''. In 2000, he was elected president of the [[American Historical Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historians.org/info/AHA_History/Efoner.htm|title=Eric Foner}}</ref> He was elected to the [[American Philosophical Society]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.amphilsoc.org/blog/election-new-members-2018-spring-meeting |title = Election of New Members at the 2018 Spring Meeting}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFoner was born in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], the son of Jewish parents Liza (n\u00e9e Kraitz), a high school art teacher, and historian [[Jack D. Foner]], who was active in the trade union movement and the campaign for civil rights for [[African Americans]]. Eric Foner describes his father as his \"first great teacher,\" and recalls how,\n\n<blockquote>deprived of his livelihood while I was growing up, he supported our family as a freelance lecturer. ... Listening to his lectures, I came to appreciate how present concerns can be illuminated by the study of the past\u2014how the repression of the [[McCarthy era]] recalled the days of the [[Alien and Sedition Acts]], the civil rights movement needed to be viewed in light of the great struggles of Black and White abolitionists, and in the brutal suppression of the [[Philippine insurrection]] at the turn of the century could be found the antecedents of [[Vietnam War|American intervention in Vietnam]]. I also imbibed a way of thinking about the past in which visionaries and underdogs\u2014[[Tom Paine]], [[Wendell Phillips]], [[Eugene V. Debs]], and [[W.&nbsp;E.&nbsp;B. Du Bois]]\u2014were as central to the historical drama as presidents and captains of industry, and how a commitment to [[social justice]] could infuse one's attitudes towards the past.<ref>Jon Wiener, [https://www.historians.org/perspectives/issues/2000/0004/0004mem2.cfm \"In Memoriam: Jack D. Foner.\" ''Perspectives'' (April 2000) \u2013 American Historical Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref></blockquote>\n\nFoner went to Columbia University for his BA; he was majoring in [[physics]] until he took a year-long seminar with James P. Shenton on the Civil War and Reconstruction during his junior year. \"It probably determined that most of my career has been focused on that period,\" he recalled years later.<ref>Eric Watkin, [http://www.columbia.edu/cu/record/archives/vol22/vol22_iss3/Professor_Shenton.html \"Professor James P. Shenton '49: History's Happy Warrior\"], ''Columbia College Today'' 22:3 (Summer 1996)</ref> A year later, in 1963, Foner graduated ''summa cum laude'' as a history major. He studied at [[Oxford University|Oxford]] as a [[Kellett Fellowship|Kellett Fellow]]; he received a BA from [[Oriel College, Oxford|Oriel College]] in 1965, where he was a member of the college's 1966 [[University Challenge]] winning team, though he did not appear in the final, having already returned to the US.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.college.columbia.edu/cct_archive/jul02/jul02_profile_foner.html | title=Columbia College Today}}</ref>  Foner returned to Columbia for his PhD, where he worked under [[Richard Hofstadter]]; he finished in 1969.\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1973 to 1982, Foner served as a professor in the history department at [[City College of New York|City College]] and Graduate Center at [[City University of New York]]. In 1976 and 1977, he was a visiting professor of American History at Princeton University. In 1980, he was [[Pitt Professor of American History and Institutions]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].\n\nAppointed the [[DeWitt Clinton]] Professor of History at Columbia University in 1988, a chair previously held by his mentor Richard Hofstadter, Foner specializes in mid-19th-century US history.  He was elected president of the [[Organization of American Historians]] (1993\u20131994), and of the [[American Historical Association]] (2000).\nHe is one of only two persons to serve as president of the Organization of American Historians, American Historical Association, and Society of American Historians.\n\n===Writing on the Reconstruction Era===\nFoner is a leading authority on the Reconstruction Era.  In a seminal essay in ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'' in October 1982, later reprinted in ''Reviews in American History'', Foner wrote,\n\n<blockquote>In the past twenty years, no period of American history has been the subject of a more thoroughgoing reevaluation than Reconstruction\u2014the violent, dramatic, and still controversial era following the Civil War.  Race relations, politics, social life, and economic change during Reconstruction have all been reinterpreted in the light of changed attitudes toward the place of blacks within American society.  If historians have not yet forged a fully satisfying portrait of Reconstruction as a whole, the traditional interpretation that dominated historical writing for much of this century has irrevocably been laid to rest.<ref>Foner, Eric, \"The New View Of Reconstruction,\" ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'', October/November 1983, Volume 34, Issue 6.</ref> </blockquote>\n\nThat year, he gave the [[Walter L. Fleming]] Lectures in southern history, which were later published as ''Nothing but Freedom: Emancipation and Its Legacy.''\n\nIn 1988, Foner published his definitive book ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877.''  It won the [[Bancroft Prize]], the [[Francis Parkman Prize]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' Book Award, the [[Avery O. Craven]] Prize, and the [[Lionel Trilling]] Prize.\n\n\"Foner has established himself as the leading authority on the Reconstruction period,\" wrote historian Michael Perman in reviewing ''Reconstruction''.  \"This book is not simply a distillation of the secondary literature; it is a masterly account \u2013 broad in scope as well as rich in detail and insight.<ref name=\"reconstruction73\" /> \"This is history written on a grand scale, a masterful treatment of one of the most complex periods of American history,\" [[David Herbert Donald]] wrote in ''[[The New Republic]]''. C. Vann Woodward, in ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', wrote, \"Eric Foner has put together this terrible story with greater cogency and power, I believe, than has been brought to the subject heretofore.\"<ref>[https://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/winter12/features5 Columbia College Today: \"Freedom Writer\"].</ref>  Foner has continued to lecture widely on Reconstruction and published several shorter versions of his major book, including ''A Short History of Reconstruction, 1863\u20131877'' (1990) and ''America's Reconstruction: People and Politics After the Civil War'' (1995).\n\nIn a 2009 essay, Foner pondered whether Reconstruction might have turned out differently.\n\n<blockquote>\"It is wrong to think that, during the Civil War, [[Presidency of Abraham Lincoln|President Lincoln]] embraced a single 'plan' of Reconstruction,\" he wrote. \"Lincoln had always been willing to work closely with all factions of his party, including the Radicals on numerous occasions. I think it is quite plausible to imagine Lincoln and Congress agreeing to a Reconstruction policy encompassing basic civil rights for blacks (as was enacted in 1866) plus limited black suffrage, along the lines he proposed just before his death.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120616125206/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/if-lincoln-hadn%E2%80%99t-died \"If Lincoln Hadn't Died...\"], ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'', 2009</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2015|reason=Only the first sentence of the quote appears at the link}}</blockquote>\n\nFoner's recent short summary of his views was published in ''The New York Times'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|title=Why Reconstruction Matters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/29/opinion/sunday/why-reconstruction-matters.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=March 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Confederate statues===\nIn a  ''New York Times'' op-ed, he criticised President [[Donald Trump]]'s tweet calling for the preservation of Confederate monuments and heritage, stating that they represented and glorified [[white supremacy]] rather than collective heritage.<ref>Foner, Eric. (Aug. 21, 2017) \u201c[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/20/opinion/confederate-statues-american-history.html Confederate Statues and 'Our' History.]\" ''The New York Times''.  Retrieved Jan. 2, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Secession and the Soviet Union===\nAs a visiting professor in Moscow in the early 1990s, Foner compared secessionist forces in the USSR with the secession movement in the US in the 1860s. In a February 1991 article, Foner noted that the Baltic states claimed the right to secede because they had been unwillingly annexed. In addition, he believed that the Soviet Union did not protect minorities while it tried to nationalize the republics. Foner identified a threat to existing minority groups within the Baltic states, who were in turn threatened by the new nationalist movements.<ref name=\"baltic\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=19lNAQAAIAAJ \"Secession of Baltic States?\"], Eric Foner, ''The Nation'', 11 February 1991, Volume 252</ref>\n\n===Exhibitions and testimony===\nWith Olivia Mahoney, chief curator at the Chicago History Museum,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagohistory.org/documents/home/aboutus/pressroom/biographies/CHM-OliviaMahoney.pdf|title=Olivia Mahoney|work=About Us|publisher=Chicago History|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925060628/http://chicagohistory.org/documents/home/aboutus/pressroom/biographies/CHM-OliviaMahoney.pdf |archivedate=2010-09-25}}</ref> Foner curated two prize-winning exhibitions on American history: ''A House Divided: America in the Age of Lincoln'', which opened at the [[Chicago History Museum]] in 1990, and ''America's Reconstruction: People and Politics After the Civil War,'' a traveling exhibit that opened at the [[Virginia Historical Society]] in 1995. He revised the presentation of American history at the [[Hall of Presidents]] at [[Walt Disney World]]'s [[Magic Kingdom]], and [[Great Moments with Mr. Lincoln]] at [[Disneyland]]. He has served as consultant to several [[National Park Service]] historical sites and historical museums.\n\nFoner served as an expert witness for the [[University of Michigan]]'s defense of [[affirmative action]] in its undergraduate and law school admissions (''[[Gratz v. Bollinger]]'' and ''[[Grutter v. Bollinger]]'') considered by the US Supreme Court in 2003.\n\n===Editorial boards===\nFoner serves on the editorial boards of ''[[Past & Present (journal)|Past and Present]]'' and ''[[The Nation (U.S. periodical)|The Nation]]''.\n\nFoner has written for ''The New York Times'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[London Review of Books]]'', and other publications. In addition, he has spoken about history on television and radio, including ''[[Charlie Rose]]'', ''Book Notes'', and ''[[All Things Considered]].'' He has appeared in historical documentaries on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] and [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]]. Foner contributed an essay and conversation with [[John Sayles]] in ''Past Imperfect: History According to the Movies'', published by the Society of American Historians in 1995. He was the historian in ''Freedom: A History of US'' on PBS in 2003.\n\n===Media appearances===\nFoner has appeared frequently on popular media to discuss US history:\n* {{cite web|title=Eric Foner: Eric Foner says Abraham Lincoln didn't see slavery as a fundamental problem confronting America until well into his career |url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/re8ih2/the-colbert-report-eric-foner|website=The Colbert Report|publisher=Comedy Central|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=13 November 2015}}\n* {{cite web|title=I's on Edjukashun \u2013 Texas School Board: Eric Foner disagrees with the Texas school board's decision to give students a completely misleading view of history |url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/wuyjzf/the-colbert-report-i-s-on-edjukashun---texas-school-board|website=The Colbert Report|publisher=Comedy Central|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=13 November 2015}}\n* {{cite web|title=Exclusive \u2013 The Weakest Lincoln: In this extended clip, Judge Andrew Napolitano and Abraham Lincoln compete in a numbers game about the true cost of the Civil War |url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/abrzf9/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-exclusive---the-weakest-lincoln|website=The Daily Show|publisher=Comedy Central|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=13 November 2015}}\n\n==Reception==\nThe professional awards which Foner has received indicate the respect given his work. Journalist [[Nat Hentoff]] described his ''Story of American Freedom'' \"an indispensable book that should be read in every school in the land.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3812/is_200003/ai_n8891943 |work=The New Crisis |title=Books |first=Tom |last=Mansart |year=2000}}</ref> \"Eric Foner is one of the most prolific, creative, and influential American historians of the past 20 years,\" according to ''The Washington Post''. His work is \"brilliant, important\" a reviewer wrote in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/product-description/0393319628 |title=The Story of American Freedom: Eric Foner: 9780393319620: Amazon.com: Books |date= |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''The Story of American Freedom'' in the ''New York Review of Books'', [[Theodore Draper]] disagreed with Foner's conclusions:\n\n<blockquote>If the story of American freedom is told largely from the perspective of blacks and women, especially the former, it is not going to be a pretty tale. Yet most Americans thought of themselves not only as free but as the freest people in the world.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/1999/sep/23/freedom-and-its-discontents |title=Freedom and Its Discontents by Theodore H. Draper |journal=The New York Review of Books |date=1999-09-23 |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nJohn Patrick Diggins of the [[City University of New York]] wrote that Foner's ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877'', was a \"magisterial\" and \"moving\" narrative, but compared Foner's \"unforgiving\" view of America for its [[racist]] past to his notably different views on the fall of communism and Soviet history.<ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2751/is_2002_Fall/ai_92042423/print John Patrick Diggins, \"Review: Eric Foner, ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877''\"], ''The National Interest'', Fall 2002</ref>\n\nFoner's most recent book ''Gateway to Freedom: The Hidden History of the Underground Railroad'' (2015) was judged \"Intellectually probing and emotionally resonant by the ''Los Angeles Times.''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Wendy|title=Review 'Gateway to Freedom' reveals underground railroad history|url=http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-eric-foner-20150111-story.html|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=January 8, 2015}}</ref> His previous book ''The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery'' (2010) was described by ''Library Journal'' as \"Original and compelling. \u2026 In the vast library on Lincoln, Foner's book stands out as the most sensible and sensitive reading of Lincoln's lifetime involvement with slavery and the most insightful assessment of Lincoln's\u2014and indeed America's\u2014imperative to move toward freedom lest it be lost. An essential work for all Americans.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Fiery Trial|publisher=W.W. Norton & Co.|isbn=978-0-393-34066-2|date=2011-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 1989, Foner received the Avery O. Craven Award from the [[Organization of American Historians]]. In 1991, Foner received the Great Teacher Award from the ''Society of Columbia Graduates''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/vnews/display.v/ART/2004/09/30/415bac2847275?in_archive=1 |accessdate=April 25, 2006 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In 1995, he was named [https://www.pbs.org/moyers/journal/11072008/profile2.html Scholar of the Year] by the New York Council for the Humanities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyhumanities.org/ |title=New York Council for the Humanities |publisher=Nyhumanities.org |date= |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref> He is an elected fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] and of the [[British Academy]].\n\nFoner has taught at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]] as Pitt Professor of American History and Institutions, at [[Oxford University]] as [[Harmsworth Professorship of American History|Harmsworth Professor of American History]], where he is also an honorary fellow of the [[Rothermere American Institute]], and at [[Moscow State University]] as [[Fulbright]] Professor.\n\nIn 2007, the alumni of Columbia College voted to give Foner the [[John Jay]] Award for Distinguished Professional Achievement. In 2011, his book ''The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery'' won the [[Pulitzer Prize]] for history, the [[Bancroft Prize]] and the [[Lincoln Prize]].\n\nFoner has been awarded honorary doctorates from [[Iona College (New York)|Iona College]]; the [[State University of New York, Purchase]];  [[Queen Mary University of London]], [[Dartmouth College]], and [[Lehigh University]].\n\nFoner was inducted as a Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]] and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State's highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 2009 as a Bicentennial Laureate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelincolnacademyofillinois.org/4632-2/#toggle-id-7|title=Laureates by Year \u2013 The Lincoln Academy of Illinois|website=The Lincoln Academy of Illinois|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Foner was awarded the Roy Rosenzweig Distinguished Service Award from the Organization of American Historians which goes to an individual or individuals whose contributions have significantly enriched our understanding and appreciation of American history.<ref>https://www.oah.org/awards/uncategorized-awards/distinguished-service/winners/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1965 Foner married screenwriter [[Naomi Foner Gyllenhaal]], who he divorced in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imdb.com/name/nm1197217/|title=Eric Foner|work=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982 Foner married [[Lynn Garafola]],<ref>[http://www.barnard.columbia.edu/newnews/news050205b.html Barnard College Newscenter<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060228013439/http://www.barnard.columbia.edu/newnews/news050205b.html |date=2006-02-28 }}</ref> professor of dance at [[Barnard College]] and dance critic, historian, and curator. They have one daughter.\n\nEric Foner's paternal uncles are the late [[Marxist historiography|Marxist labor historian]] [[Philip S. Foner]] (his father's twin brother) and labor activists [[Henry Foner]] and [[Moe Foner]]. [[Nancy Foner]] is his cousin.\n\n==Comments on teaching==\nFoner has frequently explored teaching moments that historians can use. He wrote, \"Like all momentous events, September 11 is a remarkable teaching opportunity. But only if we use it to open rather than to close debate. Critical intellectual analysis is our responsibility\u2014to ourselves and to our students.\"<ref>\"Rethinking American History in a Post-9/11 World\" [http://hnn.us/articles/6961.html ''History News Network'']</ref>\n\n\"[S]uccessful teaching rests both on a genuine and selfless concern for students and on the ability to convey to them a love of history.\"<ref>Eric Foner, ''Who Owns History? Rethinking the Past in a Changing World,'' (Farrar, Straus & Giroux: 2002), p.&nbsp;7.</ref>\n\n\"In a global age, the forever-unfinished story of American freedom must become a conversation with the entire world, not a complacent monologue with ourselves.\"<ref>\"American Freedom in a Global Age\" Presidential Address to the [http://www.historians.org/info/AHA_History/Efoner.htm American Historical Association annual meeting], January 2001.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Books===\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?113124-1/the-story-american-freedom ''Booknotes'' interview with Foner on ''The Story of American Freedom'', November 15, 1998], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?190803-1/forever-free-story-emancipation-reconstruction Presentation by Foner and Joshua Brown on ''Forever Free'', January 12, 2006], [[C-SPAN]]| video3 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?296968-1/the-fiery-trial Presentation by Foner on ''The Fiery Trial'', October 27, 2010], [[C-SPAN]]| video4 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?301645-7/the-fiery-trial Interview with Foner on ''The Fiery Trial'', September 24, 2011], [[C-SPAN]]| video5 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?301645-6/the-fiery-trial Presentation by Foner on ''The Fiery Trial'', September 24, 2011], [[C-SPAN]]| video6 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?324420-1/after-words-eric-foner ''After Words'' interview with Foner on ''Gateway to Freedom'', March 21, 2015], [[C-SPAN]]| video7 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?328440-1/underground-railroad Presentation by Foner on ''Gateway to Freedom'', September 30, 2015], [[C-SPAN]]| video8 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?464679-1/eric-foner-discusses-the-founding Presentation by Foner on ''The Second Founding'', October 2, 2019], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n* {{cite book|title=Free Soil, Free Labor, Free Men: The Ideology of the Republican Party Before the Civil War|year=1995|origyear=1970|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-509497-8}} Reissued with a new preface.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HUqJPUyS83AC|title=Free Soil, Free Labor, Free Men|isbn=978-0-19-509497-8|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=1995-04-20}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=America's Black Past: A Reader in Afro-American History|url=https://archive.org/details/americasblackpas00fone|url-access=registration|year=1970|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York}}, editor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/America_s_black_past.html?id=LDwOAQAAMAAJ|title=America's black past|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1970}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Nat Turner|year=1971|publisher=Prentice-Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|isbn=978-0-13-933143-5|url=https://archive.org/details/natturner0000fone}}, editor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Nat_Turner.html?id=oTcSAAAAYAAJ|title=Nat Turner|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1971}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Tom Paine and Revolutionary America|year=1976|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-501986-5|url=https://archive.org/details/tompainerevoluti00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Tom_Paine_and_Revolutionary_America.html?id=OyFF1M8_VDAC|title=Tom Paine and Revolutionary America|isbn=978-0-19-517486-1|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2005}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Politics and Ideology in the Age of the Civil War|year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-502781-5|url=https://archive.org/details/politicsideology00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Politics_and_Ideology_in_the_Age_of_the.html?id=rQSYk-LWTxcC|title=Politics and Ideology in the Age of the Civil War|isbn=978-0-19-972708-7|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=1980-10-02}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Nothing but Freedom: Emancipation and Its Legacy|url=https://archive.org/details/nothingbutfreedo00eric|url-access=registration|year=1983|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|location=Baton Rouge|isbn=978-0-8071-1118-5}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Nothing_But_Freedom.html?id=F0ay2hkUZiwC|title=Nothing But Freedom|isbn=978-0-8071-3525-9|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=September 2007}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877|year=1988|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-015851-4|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780060158514}} Political history; and winner, in 1989, of the [[Bancroft Prize]], the [[Francis Parkman Prize]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' Book Award, the Avery O. Craven Prize, and the Lionel Trilling Prize.\n* {{cite book|title=A Short History of Reconstruction, 1863\u20131877|year=1990|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-096431-3|url=https://archive.org/details/shorthistoryofre00eric}} An abridgement of ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/shorthistoryofre00eric|url-access=registration|title=A Short History of Reconstruction|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-096431-3|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=1990-01-10}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=A House Divided: America in the Age of Lincoln|year=1990|others=with Olivia Mahoney|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|location=Chicago|isbn=978-0-393-02755-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/housedividedamer0000fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/A_House_Divided.html?id=4AO9QgAACAAJ|title=A House Divided|isbn=978-0-393-02755-6|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|last2=Mahoney|first2=Olivia|year=1990}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Reader's Companion to American History|year=1991|others=ed. with [[John A. Garraty]]|publisher=Houghton-Mifflin|location=Boston|isbn=978-0-395-51372-9|url=https://archive.org/details/readerscompanion00fone}}, editor<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/readerscompanion00fone|url-access=registration|title=The Reader's Companion to American History|publisher=Houghton-Mifflin|isbn=978-0-395-51372-9|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|last2=Garraty|first2=John Arthur|year=1991}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Tocsin of Freedom: The Black Leadership of Radical Reconstruction|year=1992|publisher=Gettysburg College|location=Gettysburg, Pa.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Tocsin_of_Freedom.html?id=FZENogEACAAJ|title=The tocsin of freedom|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1992}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Slavery and Freedom in Nineteenth-Century America|year=1994|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-952266-8}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Slavery and Freedom in Nineteenth-Century America (Inaugural Lectures (University of Oxford)): Eric Foner: 9780199522668: Amazon.com: Books|isbn = 978-0-19-952266-8|last1 = Foner|first1 = Eric|year = 1994}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=America's Reconstruction: People and Politics After the Civil War|year=1995|others=with Olivia Mahoney|publisher=HarperPerennial|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-055346-3|url=https://archive.org/details/americasreconstr00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/America_s_Reconstruction.html?id=YNpHv2LQ8nYC|title=America's Reconstruction|isbn=978-0-8071-2234-1|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|last2=Mahoney|first2=Olivia|date=1997-06-01}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Freedom's Lawmakers: A Directory of Black Officeholders During Reconstruction|year=1996|edition=rev.|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|location=Baton Rouge|isbn=978-0-8071-2082-8}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Freedom_s_Lawmakers.html?id=F2MYAAAAIAAJ|title=Freedom's Lawmakers|isbn=978-0-19-507406-2|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1993}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The New American History|year=1997|edition=rev.|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-1-56639-551-9}}, editor<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_New_American_History.html?id=J7hnUHplC7wC|title=The New American History|isbn=978-1-56639-552-6|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1997}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Story of American Freedom|year=1998|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-04665-6|url=https://archive.org/details/storyofamericanf00fone}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_story_of_American_freedom.html?id=oLJ1AAAAMAAJ|title=The story of American freedom|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1994}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Who Owns History?: Rethinking the Past in a Changing World|year=2002|publisher=Hill and Wang|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8090-9704-3|url=https://archive.org/details/whoownshistoryre00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3I-Z8KW5REC&printsec=copyright#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Who Owns History?|isbn=978-1-4299-2392-7|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=2003-04-16}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Give Me Liberty!: An American History|year=2004|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-97872-8}} A survey of United States history, published with companion volumes of documents.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Give_Me_Liberty.html?id=OTGXGyeVdPEC|title=Give Me Liberty!|isbn=978-0-393-92782-5|date=2005-12-01}}</ref>\n* ''Voices of Freedom: A Documentary History'', {{ISBN|978-0-393-92503-6}} (vol. 1), and {{ISBN|978-0-393-92504-3}} (2 vols.).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Voices_of_Freedom.html?id=QQCFNwAACAAJ|title=Voices of Freedom|isbn=978-0-393-92503-6|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Voices_of_Freedom.html?id=BrTtAAAAMAAJ|title=Voices of Freedom|isbn=978-0-393-93108-2|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2008}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Forever Free: The Story of Emancipation and Reconstruction|year=2005|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-375-40259-3|url=https://archive.org/details/foreverfreestory00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/foreverfreestory00fone|url-access=registration|title=Forever Free|publisher=Knopf|isbn=978-0-375-40259-3|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2005}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Our Lincoln: New Perspectives on Lincoln and his World|year=2008|publisher=[[W.W. Norton]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-06756-9|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780393067569}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Our_Lincoln.html?id=gRF-PwAACAAJ|title=Our Lincoln|isbn=978-0-393-33705-1|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2009}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery|year=2010|publisher=[[W.W. Norton]]|location=New York}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Fiery_Trial_Abraham_Lincoln_and_Amer.html?id=earytjxi6pEC|title=The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery|isbn=978-0-393-08082-7|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=2011-09-26}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Gateway to Freedom: The Hidden History of the Underground Railroad|year=2015|publisher=[[W.W. Norton & Co.]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-24407-6|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/gatewaytofreedom0000fone|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite book|title=Battles for Freedom: The Use and Abuse of American History|year=2017|publisher=[[I.B. Tauris]]|location=|isbn=978-1-78453-769-2|pages=|url=}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Second Founding: How the Civil War and Reconstruction Remade the Constitution|year=2019|publisher=[[W. W. Norton]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-65258-1}}\n\nSome of his books have been translated into Portuguese, Italian, and Chinese.\n\n===Selected articles===\n* {{cite journal |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Radical Individualism in America: Revolution to Civil War |journal=Literature of Liberty |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=1\u201331 |date=July\u2013September 1978 |url=http://oll.libertyfund.org/?option=com_staticxt&staticfile=show.php%3Ftitle=909&chapter=99730&layout=html&Itemid=27 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The New View of Reconstruction |journal=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=34 |issue=6 |date=October\u2013November 1983 |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/new-view-reconstruction |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Why Is There No Socialism in the United States? |journal=[[History Workshop Journal]] |volume=17 |issue= 17|pages=57\u201380 |date=Spring 1984 |jstor=4288545 |ref=harv |doi=10.1093/hwj/17.1.57 }}\n* {{cite news|last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The South's Inner Civil War |work=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=40 |issue=2 |date=March 1989 |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/south%E2%80%99s-inner-civil-war-0 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218233100/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/south%E2%80%99s-inner-civil-war-0 |archivedate=2013-12-18 }}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Rebel Yell |work=The Nation |date=January 27, 2000 |url=http://www.thenation.com/doc/20000214/foner}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Changing History |work=The Nation |date= September 5, 2002 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/090502nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The Century, A Nation's Eye View |work=The Nation |date=December 10, 2002 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/121002nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Not All Freedom Is Made In America |work=The New York Times|date=April 13, 2003 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/041303nytimes.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Dare Call It Treason |work=The Nation |date=June 2, 2003 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/060203nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Diversity Over Justice |work=The Nation |date=June 26, 2003 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/072603nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Rethinking American History in a Post-9/11 World |work=History News Network |date=September 6, 2004 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/090604hnn.html}}\n* {{cite web|last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Expert Report of Eric Foner: from Gratz, et al. v. Bollinger, et al. |url=http://www.vpcomm.umich.edu/admissions/legal/expert/foner.html |date=2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060829030100/http://www.vpcomm.umich.edu/admissions/legal/expert/foner.html |archivedate=August 29, 2006}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=He's the Worst Ever |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 3, 2006 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/01/AR2006120101509.html}} Column on George W. Bush.\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=If Lincoln Hadn't Died... |work=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=58 |issue=6 |date=Winter 2009 |url=http://www.americanheritage.com}}\n* {{cite news|last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The Civil War in 'Postracial' America |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/101011nation.html |work=The Nation |date=October 10, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001073757/http://ericfoner.com/articles/101011nation.html |archivedate=October 1, 2011}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The Supreme Court and the history of reconstruction \u2013 and vice-versa |journal=[[Columbia Law Review]] |volume=112 |issue=7 |pages=1585\u20131606 |publisher=[[Columbia Law School]] |jstor=41708159 |date=November 2012 |url=http://columbialawreview.org/the-supreme-court-and-the-history-of-reconstruction-and-vice-versa/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015834/http://columbialawreview.org/the-supreme-court-and-the-history-of-reconstruction-and-vice-versa/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-11-17 |ref=harv }} [https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015028/http://columbialawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/1585-1606.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The Emancipation of Abe Lincoln |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/01/opinion/the-emancipation-of-abe-lincoln.html?ref=opinion |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 1, 2013}}\n* (Additional articles available at [http://ericfoner.com/articles/index.html EricFoner.com])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |jstor=42895561|title=Fate and Freedom in History: The Two Worlds of Eric Foner|journal=The National Interest|issue=69|pages=79\u201390|last1=Diggins|first1=John Patrick|year=2002}}\n* {{cite journal |jstor=23522901|last1=Smith|first1=John David|title=Reviewed work: Who Owns History? Rethinking the Past in a Changing World, Eric Foner|journal=The North Carolina Historical Review|volume=80|issue=3|pages=400\u2013401|year=2003}}\n* {{cite journal |jstor=10.1525/tph.2003.25.1.91|doi=10.1525/tph.2003.25.1.91|title=Book Reviews|journal=The Public Historian|volume=25|issue=1|pages=91\u2013109|year=2003}}\n* Katz, Jamie. \"Freedom Writer: Pulitzer Prize-winning Columbia historian Eric Foner '63, '69 GSAS personifies the great teacher and scholar who approaches his calling with moral urgency,\" ''Columbia College Today'', Winter 2012\u20132013. [https://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/winter12/features5 online]\n* Snowman, Daniel, \"Eric Foner\", ''History Today'' Volume 50, Issue 1, January 2000, pp.&nbsp;26\u201327 .\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.ericfoner.com/index.html EricFoner.com] \u2013 Professor Foner's homepage\n* [http://isbn.nu/aisbn/foner%20eric Books written by Eric Foner or edited or introduced by him]\n* [http://www.historians.org/info/AHA_History/efonerbibliography.htm American Historical Association] \u2013 Bibliography of Foner's Books\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060327155543/http://www.fathom.com/feature/121845/ Fathom Source for Online Learning Foner discusses influential history books he has read.]\n* [http://www.films42.com/feature/november_feature.asp Excerpt from Eric Foner essay on the [[John Sayles]] film, ''[[Matewan]]'' in the book ''Past Imperfect: History According to the Movies'' edited by historian Mark C. Carnes]\n* [http://www.nationalreview.com/comment/comment-radosh071002.asp ''The Left's Lion: Eric Foner's History''] \u2013 by [[Ronald Radosh]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060829030100/http://www.vpcomm.umich.edu/admissions/legal/expert/foner.html Expert report] by Eric Foner for University of Michigan Affirmative Action cases\n* {{Internet Archive film clip|id=openmind_ep452|description=\"The Open Mind \u2013 A Historian's 'Story of American Freedom,' Part I (1999)\"}}\n* {{Internet Archive film clip|id=openmind_ep453|description=\"The Open Mind \u2013 A Historian's 'Story of American Freedom,' Part II (1999)\"}}\n\n===Lectures===\n* Lectures from \"The Civil War and Reconstruction\" course series (videos): [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLSuwqsAnJMtyg3ROpOADVoW1NV5kmskFM 1850\u20131861], [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLSuwqsAnJMtxQzYD78gR_17YLH4A3wXHP 1861\u20131865], [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLSuwqsAnJMtypyVdc5V3dz9yWo6pIrGvT 1865\u20131890]\n* [http://www.kwls.org/podcasts/eric_foner_2009_who_owns_histo/ Eric Foner lecture \"Who Owns History?\" from the 2009 Key West Literary Seminar (audio recording)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050525023336/http://mitworld.mit.edu/video/263/ ''\"The Story of American Freedom: 1776\u20132005\"''] (video): MIT SPURS/Humphrey Program sponsored lecture by Eric Foner from the series \"Myths About America.\"\n\n===Interviews===\n* interviews with on [[Democracy Now!]] about Foner's 2015 book [http://books.wwnorton.com/books/Gateway-to-Freedom/ Gateway to Freedom: The Hidden History of the Underground Railroad] (et al.):\n** [http://www.democracynow.org/2015/3/11/gateway_to_freedom_historian_eric_foner part 1], begins ~35:38 in [http://traffic.libsyn.com/democracynow/dn2015-0311-1.mp3 audio] and [http://publish.dvlabs.com/democracynow/ipod/dn2015-0311.mp4 video]\n** [http://www.democracynow.org/blog/2015/3/11/civil_war_historian_eric_foner_on part 2]: [http://traffic.libsyn.com/democracynow/wx2015-0311_foner.mp3 audio], [http://publish.dvlabs.com/democracynow/ipod/wx2015-0311_foner.mp4 video]\n* [https://www.jacobinmag.com/2015/03/eric-foner-interview-reconstruction-slavery/ The Second American Revolution: Historian Eric Foner on slavery, freedom, and contemporary US politics]. ''[[Jacobin (magazine)|Jacobin]].'' March 28, 2015.\n* {{C-SPAN|Eric Foner}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lX0ar575Qq0 On Contact: Creative Forgetfulness with Eric Foner] (interviewed by [[Chris Hedges]]). RT America on YouTube, Sep 18, 2017\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Eliot Freidson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Pitt Professor of American History and Institutions]]|years=1980\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Douglass North]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Lewis Gaddis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Professor of American History|Harmsworth Professor of American History]]|years=1993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Dallek]]}}\n{{s-npo|pro}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lawrence W. Levine]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the<br />[[Organization of American Historians]]|years=1993\u20131994}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gary B. Nash]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Darnton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[American Historical Association]]|years=2000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Wm. Roger Louis]]}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Kolchin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bancroft Prize]]|years=1989|with=[[Edmund Morgan (historian)|Edmund Morgan]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Neil R. McMillen]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael S. Sherry]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James Merrell]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael Burlingame (historian)|Michael Burlingame]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lincoln Prize]]|years=2011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Elizabeth D. Leonard]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Liaquat Ahamed]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Pulitzer Prize for History]]|years=2011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Manning Marable]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{American Historical Association presidents}}\n{{PulitzerPrize HistoryAuthors 2001\u20132025}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foner, Eric}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Southern United States]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Reconstruction Era]]\n[[Category:Historians of race relations]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for History winners]]\n[[Category:Columbia College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Oriel College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Jewish American historians]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Historical Association]]\n[[Category:Winners of the Lincoln Prize]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Professors of American History]]\n[[Category:The Nation (U.S. magazine) people]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Philosophical Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American historian}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Eric Foner\n| image              = Eric Foner, New York City, New York, September 15, 2009.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| alt                = A grey-haired bespectacled man wearing a light blue shirt and sitting on a chair behind a desk; behind him is a bookshelf and a wall mounted with certificates and awards\n| caption            = Foner at his [[New York City]] office in 2009\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age |mf=yes|1943|2|7}}\n| birth_place        = {{nowrap|[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], US}}\n| alma_mater         = {{ubl | [[Columbia University]] | [[Oriel College, Oxford]]}}\n| awards             = {{ubl | [[Bancroft Prize]] (1989; 2011) | [[Lincoln Prize]] (2011) | [[Pulitzer Prize]] (2011)}}\n| parents            = {{hlist | [[Jack D. Foner]] | Liza Kraitz}}\n| spouse             = {{ubl | {{marriage|[[Naomi Foner Gyllenhaal|Naomi Achs]]|1965|1977|reason=divorced}} | {{marriage|[[Lynn Garafola]]|1980}}}}\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = [[Richard Hofstadter]]\n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = History\n| sub_discipline     = [[History of the United States|American]] [[political history]]\n| workplaces         = {{ubl | [[City College of New York]] | [[Columbia University]]}}\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Elizabeth Hinton]]\n* [[Mae Ngai]]\n}}\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = ''[[The Fiery Trial]]'' (2010)\n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n}}\n\n'''Eric Foner''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|o\u028a|n|\u0259r}}; born February 7, 1943) is an American [[historian]]. He writes extensively on [[History of the United States|American]] [[political history]], the history of freedom, the early [[History of the United States Republican Party|history of the Republican Party]], [[African-American]] biography, [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]], and [[historiography]], and has been a member of the faculty at the [[Columbia University]] Department of History since 1982. He is the author of several popular textbooks. According to the Open Syllabus Project, Foner is the most frequently cited author on college syllabi for history courses.<ref>https://opensyllabus.org/results-list/authors?size=50&fields=History</ref>\n\nFoner is a leading contemporary historian of the  Reconstruction period, having published ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877'' in 1989 and more than 10 other books on the topic.<ref name=\"reconstruction73\">Perman, Michael. \"Eric Foner's Reconstruction: A Finished Revolution\". ''Reviews in American History,'' Vol. 17, No. 1. (Mar., 1989), pp. 73\u201378.</ref> His online courses on \"The Civil War and Reconstruction\", published in 2014, are available from Columbia University on ColumbiaX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edx.org/xseries/civil-war-reconstruction|title=The Civil War and Reconstruction|date=2015-01-07|website=edX|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Foner's ''[[The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery]]'' (2010) won the [[Pulitzer Prize for History]], the [[Lincoln Prize]], and the [[Bancroft Prize]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/house-divided/2011/02/prestigious_lincoln_prize_goes.html |work=The Washington Post |title=Prestigious Lincoln Prize goes to Eric Foner}}</ref><ref>http://newswire.ascribe.org/cgi-bin/behold.pl?ascribeid=20110210.071303&time=02%2000%20PST&year=2011&public=0{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/historian-foner-among-3-winners-of-bancroft-prize-news-hollywood-ld2dkndehfi.html |title=Historian Foner among 3 winners of Bancroft Prize |publisher=Sify.com |date=2011-03-28 |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref> Foner previously won the Bancroft in 1989 for his book ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877''. In 2000, he was elected president of the [[American Historical Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historians.org/info/AHA_History/Efoner.htm|title=Eric Foner}}</ref> He was elected to the [[American Philosophical Society]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.amphilsoc.org/blog/election-new-members-2018-spring-meeting |title = Election of New Members at the 2018 Spring Meeting}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFoner was born in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], the son of Jewish parents Liza (n\u00e9e Kraitz), a high school art teacher, and historian [[Jack D. Foner]], who was active in the trade union movement and the campaign for civil rights for [[African Americans]]. Eric Foner describes his father as his \"first great teacher,\" and recalls how,\n\n<blockquote>deprived of his livelihood while I was growing up, he supported our family as a freelance lecturer. ... Listening to his lectures, I came to appreciate how present concerns can be illuminated by the study of the past\u2014how the repression of the [[McCarthy era]] recalled the days of the [[Alien and Sedition Acts]], the civil rights movement needed to be viewed in light of the great struggles of Black and White abolitionists, and in the brutal suppression of the [[Philippine insurrection]] at the turn of the century could be found the antecedents of [[Vietnam War|American intervention in Vietnam]]. I also imbibed a way of thinking about the past in which visionaries and underdogs\u2014[[Tom Paine]], [[Wendell Phillips]], [[Eugene V. Debs]], and [[W.&nbsp;E.&nbsp;B. Du Bois]]\u2014were as central to the historical drama as presidents and captains of industry, and how a commitment to [[social justice]] could infuse one's attitudes towards the past.<ref>Jon Wiener, [https://www.historians.org/perspectives/issues/2000/0004/0004mem2.cfm \"In Memoriam: Jack D. Foner.\" ''Perspectives'' (April 2000) \u2013 American Historical Association<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref></blockquote>\n\nFoner went to Columbia University for his BA; he was majoring in [[physics]] until he took a year-long seminar with James P. Shenton on the Civil War and Reconstruction during his junior year. \"It probably determined that most of my career has been focused on that period,\" he recalled years later.<ref>Eric Watkin, [http://www.columbia.edu/cu/record/archives/vol22/vol22_iss3/Professor_Shenton.html \"Professor James P. Shenton '49: History's Happy Warrior\"], ''Columbia College Today'' 22:3 (Summer 1996)</ref> A year later, in 1963, Foner graduated ''summa cum laude'' as a history major. He studied at [[Oxford University|Oxford]] as a [[Kellett Fellowship|Kellett Fellow]]; he received a BA from [[Oriel College, Oxford|Oriel College]] in 1965, where he was a member of the college's 1966 [[University Challenge]] winning team, though he did not appear in the final, having already returned to the US.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.college.columbia.edu/cct_archive/jul02/jul02_profile_foner.html | title=Columbia College Today}}</ref>  Foner returned to Columbia for his PhD, where he worked under [[Richard Hofstadter]]; he finished in 1969.\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1973 to 1982, Foner served as a professor in the history department at [[City College of New York|City College]] and Graduate Center at [[City University of New York]]. In 1976 and 1977, he was a visiting professor of American History at Princeton University. In 1980, he was [[Pitt Professor of American History and Institutions]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].\n\nAppointed the [[DeWitt Clinton]] Professor of History at Columbia University in 1988, a chair previously held by his mentor Richard Hofstadter, Foner specializes in mid-19th-century US history.  He was elected president of the [[Organization of American Historians]] (1993\u20131994), and of the [[American Historical Association]] (2000).\nHe is one of only two persons to serve as president of the Organization of American Historians, American Historical Association, and Society of American Historians.\n\n===Writing on the Reconstruction Era===\nFoner is a leading authority on the Reconstruction Era.  In a seminal essay in ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'' in October 1982, later reprinted in ''Reviews in American History'', Foner wrote,\n\n<blockquote>In the past twenty years, no period of American history has been the subject of a more thoroughgoing reevaluation than Reconstruction\u2014the violent, dramatic, and still controversial era following the Civil War.  Race relations, politics, social life, and economic change during Reconstruction have all been reinterpreted in the light of changed attitudes toward the place of blacks within American society.  If historians have not yet forged a fully satisfying portrait of Reconstruction as a whole, the traditional interpretation that dominated historical writing for much of this century has irrevocably been laid to rest.<ref>Foner, Eric, \"The New View Of Reconstruction,\" ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'', October/November 1983, Volume 34, Issue 6.</ref> </blockquote>\n\nThat year, he gave the [[Walter L. Fleming]] Lectures in southern history, which were later published as ''Nothing but Freedom: Emancipation and Its Legacy.''\n\nIn 1988, Foner published his definitive book ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877.''  It won the [[Bancroft Prize]], the [[Francis Parkman Prize]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' Book Award, the [[Avery O. Craven]] Prize, and the [[Lionel Trilling]] Prize.\n\n\"Foner has established himself as the leading authority on the Reconstruction period,\" wrote historian Michael Perman in reviewing ''Reconstruction''.  \"This book is not simply a distillation of the secondary literature; it is a masterly account \u2013 broad in scope as well as rich in detail and insight.<ref name=\"reconstruction73\" /> \"This is history written on a grand scale, a masterful treatment of one of the most complex periods of American history,\" [[David Herbert Donald]] wrote in ''[[The New Republic]]''. C. Vann Woodward, in ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', wrote, \"Eric Foner has put together this terrible story with greater cogency and power, I believe, than has been brought to the subject heretofore.\"<ref>[https://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/winter12/features5 Columbia College Today: \"Freedom Writer\"].</ref>  Foner has continued to lecture widely on Reconstruction and published several shorter versions of his major book, including ''A Short History of Reconstruction, 1863\u20131877'' (1990) and ''America's Reconstruction: People and Politics After the Civil War'' (1995).\n\nIn a 2009 essay, Foner pondered whether Reconstruction might have turned out differently.\n\n<blockquote>\"It is wrong to think that, during the Civil War, [[Presidency of Abraham Lincoln|President Lincoln]] embraced a single 'plan' of Reconstruction,\" he wrote. \"Lincoln had always been willing to work closely with all factions of his party, including the Radicals on numerous occasions. I think it is quite plausible to imagine Lincoln and Congress agreeing to a Reconstruction policy encompassing basic civil rights for blacks (as was enacted in 1866) plus limited black suffrage, along the lines he proposed just before his death.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120616125206/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/if-lincoln-hadn%E2%80%99t-died \"If Lincoln Hadn't Died...\"], ''[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]'', 2009</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2015|reason=Only the first sentence of the quote appears at the link}}</blockquote>\n\nFoner's recent short summary of his views was published in ''The New York Times'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|title=Why Reconstruction Matters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/29/opinion/sunday/why-reconstruction-matters.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=March 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Confederate statues===\nIn a  ''New York Times'' op-ed, he criticised President [[Donald Trump]]'s tweet calling for the preservation of Confederate monuments and heritage, stating that they represented and glorified [[white supremacy]] rather than collective heritage.<ref>Foner, Eric. (Aug. 21, 2017) \u201c[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/20/opinion/confederate-statues-american-history.html Confederate Statues and 'Our' History.]\" ''The New York Times''.  Retrieved Jan. 2, 2019.</ref>\n\n===Secession and the Soviet Union===\nAs a visiting professor in Moscow in the early 1990s, Foner compared secessionist forces in the USSR with the secession movement in the US in the 1860s. In a February 1991 article, Foner noted that the Baltic states claimed the right to secede because they had been unwillingly annexed. In addition, he believed that the Soviet Union did not protect minorities while it tried to nationalize the republics. Foner identified a threat to existing minority groups within the Baltic states, who were in turn threatened by the new nationalist movements.<ref name=\"baltic\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=19lNAQAAIAAJ \"Secession of Baltic States?\"], Eric Foner, ''The Nation'', 11 February 1991, Volume 252</ref>\n\n===Exhibitions and testimony===\nWith Olivia Mahoney, chief curator at the Chicago History Museum,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagohistory.org/documents/home/aboutus/pressroom/biographies/CHM-OliviaMahoney.pdf|title=Olivia Mahoney|work=About Us|publisher=Chicago History|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925060628/http://chicagohistory.org/documents/home/aboutus/pressroom/biographies/CHM-OliviaMahoney.pdf |archivedate=2010-09-25}}</ref> Foner curated two prize-winning exhibitions on American history: ''A House Divided: America in the Age of Lincoln'', which opened at the [[Chicago History Museum]] in 1990, and ''America's Reconstruction: People and Politics After the Civil War,'' a traveling exhibit that opened at the [[Virginia Historical Society]] in 1995. He revised the presentation of American history at the [[Hall of Presidents]] at [[Walt Disney World]]'s [[Magic Kingdom]], and [[Great Moments with Mr. Lincoln]] at [[Disneyland]]. He has served as consultant to several [[National Park Service]] historical sites and historical museums.\n\nFoner served as an expert witness for the [[University of Michigan]]'s defense of [[affirmative action]] in its undergraduate and law school admissions (''[[Gratz v. Bollinger]]'' and ''[[Grutter v. Bollinger]]'') considered by the US Supreme Court in 2003.\n\n===Editorial boards===\nFoner serves on the editorial boards of ''[[Past & Present (journal)|Past and Present]]'' and ''[[The Nation (U.S. periodical)|The Nation]]''.\n\nFoner has written for ''The New York Times'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[London Review of Books]]'', and other publications. In addition, he has spoken about history on television and radio, including ''[[Charlie Rose]]'', ''Book Notes'', and ''[[All Things Considered]].'' He has appeared in historical documentaries on [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] and [[History (U.S. TV channel)|The History Channel]]. Foner contributed an essay and conversation with [[John Sayles]] in ''Past Imperfect: History According to the Movies'', published by the Society of American Historians in 1995. He was the historian in ''Freedom: A History of US'' on PBS in 2003.\n\n===Media appearances===\nFoner has appeared frequently on popular media to discuss US history:\n* {{cite web|title=Eric Foner: Eric Foner says Abraham Lincoln didn't see slavery as a fundamental problem confronting America until well into his career |url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/re8ih2/the-colbert-report-eric-foner|website=The Colbert Report|publisher=Comedy Central|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=13 November 2015}}\n* {{cite web|title=I's on Edjukashun \u2013 Texas School Board: Eric Foner disagrees with the Texas school board's decision to give students a completely misleading view of history |url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/wuyjzf/the-colbert-report-i-s-on-edjukashun---texas-school-board|website=The Colbert Report|publisher=Comedy Central|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=13 November 2015}}\n* {{cite web|title=Exclusive \u2013 The Weakest Lincoln: In this extended clip, Judge Andrew Napolitano and Abraham Lincoln compete in a numbers game about the true cost of the Civil War |url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/abrzf9/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-exclusive---the-weakest-lincoln|website=The Daily Show|publisher=Comedy Central|date=11 February 2011|accessdate=13 November 2015}}\n\n==Reception==\nThe professional awards which Foner has received indicate the respect given his work. Journalist [[Nat Hentoff]] described his ''Story of American Freedom'' \"an indispensable book that should be read in every school in the land.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3812/is_200003/ai_n8891943 |work=The New Crisis |title=Books |first=Tom |last=Mansart |year=2000}}</ref> \"Eric Foner is one of the most prolific, creative, and influential American historians of the past 20 years,\" according to ''The Washington Post''. His work is \"brilliant, important\" a reviewer wrote in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/product-description/0393319628 |title=The Story of American Freedom: Eric Foner: 9780393319620: Amazon.com: Books |date= |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''The Story of American Freedom'' in the ''New York Review of Books'', [[Theodore Draper]] disagreed with Foner's conclusions:\n\n<blockquote>If the story of American freedom is told largely from the perspective of blacks and women, especially the former, it is not going to be a pretty tale. Yet most Americans thought of themselves not only as free but as the freest people in the world.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/1999/sep/23/freedom-and-its-discontents |title=Freedom and Its Discontents by Theodore H. Draper |journal=The New York Review of Books |date=1999-09-23 |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nJohn Patrick Diggins of the [[City University of New York]] wrote that Foner's ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877'', was a \"magisterial\" and \"moving\" narrative, but compared Foner's \"unforgiving\" view of America for its [[racist]] past to his notably different views on the fall of communism and Soviet history.<ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2751/is_2002_Fall/ai_92042423/print John Patrick Diggins, \"Review: Eric Foner, ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877''\"], ''The National Interest'', Fall 2002</ref>\n\nFoner's most recent book ''Gateway to Freedom: The Hidden History of the Underground Railroad'' (2015) was judged \"Intellectually probing and emotionally resonant by the ''Los Angeles Times.''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Wendy|title=Review 'Gateway to Freedom' reveals underground railroad history|url=http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-eric-foner-20150111-story.html|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=January 8, 2015}}</ref> His previous book ''The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery'' (2010) was described by ''Library Journal'' as \"Original and compelling. \u2026 In the vast library on Lincoln, Foner's book stands out as the most sensible and sensitive reading of Lincoln's lifetime involvement with slavery and the most insightful assessment of Lincoln's\u2014and indeed America's\u2014imperative to move toward freedom lest it be lost. An essential work for all Americans.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Fiery Trial|publisher=W.W. Norton & Co.|isbn=978-0-393-34066-2|date=2011-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 1989, Foner received the Avery O. Craven Award from the [[Organization of American Historians]]. In 1991, Foner received the Great Teacher Award from the ''Society of Columbia Graduates''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/vnews/display.v/ART/2004/09/30/415bac2847275?in_archive=1 |accessdate=April 25, 2006 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In 1995, he was named [https://www.pbs.org/moyers/journal/11072008/profile2.html Scholar of the Year] by the New York Council for the Humanities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyhumanities.org/ |title=New York Council for the Humanities |publisher=Nyhumanities.org |date= |accessdate=2013-06-07}}</ref> He is an elected fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] and of the [[British Academy]].\n\nFoner has taught at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]] as Pitt Professor of American History and Institutions, at [[Oxford University]] as [[Harmsworth Professorship of American History|Harmsworth Professor of American History]], where he is also an honorary fellow of the [[Rothermere American Institute]], and at [[Moscow State University]] as [[Fulbright]] Professor.\n\nIn 2007, the alumni of Columbia College voted to give Foner the [[John Jay]] Award for Distinguished Professional Achievement. In 2011, his book ''The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery'' won the [[Pulitzer Prize]] for history, the [[Bancroft Prize]] and the [[Lincoln Prize]].\n\nFoner has been awarded honorary doctorates from [[Iona College (New York)|Iona College]]; the [[State University of New York, Purchase]];  [[Queen Mary University of London]], [[Dartmouth College]], and [[Lehigh University]].\n\nFoner was inducted as a Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]] and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State's highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 2009 as a Bicentennial Laureate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelincolnacademyofillinois.org/4632-2/#toggle-id-7|title=Laureates by Year \u2013 The Lincoln Academy of Illinois|website=The Lincoln Academy of Illinois|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1965 Foner married screenwriter [[Naomi Foner Gyllenhaal]], who he divorced in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imdb.com/name/nm1197217/|title=Eric Foner|work=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982 Foner married [[Lynn Garafola]],<ref>[http://www.barnard.columbia.edu/newnews/news050205b.html Barnard College Newscenter<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060228013439/http://www.barnard.columbia.edu/newnews/news050205b.html |date=2006-02-28 }}</ref> professor of dance at [[Barnard College]] and dance critic, historian, and curator. They have one daughter.\n\nEric Foner's paternal uncles are the late [[Marxist historiography|Marxist labor historian]] [[Philip S. Foner]] (his father's twin brother) and labor activists [[Henry Foner]] and [[Moe Foner]]. [[Nancy Foner]] is his cousin.\n\n==Comments on teaching==\nFoner has frequently explored teaching moments that historians can use. He wrote, \"Like all momentous events, September 11 is a remarkable teaching opportunity. But only if we use it to open rather than to close debate. Critical intellectual analysis is our responsibility\u2014to ourselves and to our students.\"<ref>\"Rethinking American History in a Post-9/11 World\" [http://hnn.us/articles/6961.html ''History News Network'']</ref>\n\n\"[S]uccessful teaching rests both on a genuine and selfless concern for students and on the ability to convey to them a love of history.\"<ref>Eric Foner, ''Who Owns History? Rethinking the Past in a Changing World,'' (Farrar, Straus & Giroux: 2002), p.&nbsp;7.</ref>\n\n\"In a global age, the forever-unfinished story of American freedom must become a conversation with the entire world, not a complacent monologue with ourselves.\"<ref>\"American Freedom in a Global Age\" Presidential Address to the [http://www.historians.org/info/AHA_History/Efoner.htm American Historical Association annual meeting], January 2001.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Books===\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?113124-1/the-story-american-freedom ''Booknotes'' interview with Foner on ''The Story of American Freedom'', November 15, 1998], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?190803-1/forever-free-story-emancipation-reconstruction Presentation by Foner and Joshua Brown on ''Forever Free'', January 12, 2006], [[C-SPAN]]| video3 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?296968-1/the-fiery-trial Presentation by Foner on ''The Fiery Trial'', October 27, 2010], [[C-SPAN]]| video4 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?301645-7/the-fiery-trial Interview with Foner on ''The Fiery Trial'', September 24, 2011], [[C-SPAN]]| video5 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?301645-6/the-fiery-trial Presentation by Foner on ''The Fiery Trial'', September 24, 2011], [[C-SPAN]]| video6 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?324420-1/after-words-eric-foner ''After Words'' interview with Foner on ''Gateway to Freedom'', March 21, 2015], [[C-SPAN]]| video7 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?328440-1/underground-railroad Presentation by Foner on ''Gateway to Freedom'', September 30, 2015], [[C-SPAN]]| video8 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?464679-1/eric-foner-discusses-the-founding Presentation by Foner on ''The Second Founding'', October 2, 2019], [[C-SPAN]]}}\n* {{cite book|title=Free Soil, Free Labor, Free Men: The Ideology of the Republican Party Before the Civil War|year=1995|origyear=1970|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-509497-8}} Reissued with a new preface.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HUqJPUyS83AC|title=Free Soil, Free Labor, Free Men|isbn=978-0-19-509497-8|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=1995-04-20}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=America's Black Past: A Reader in Afro-American History|url=https://archive.org/details/americasblackpas00fone|url-access=registration|year=1970|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York}}, editor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/America_s_black_past.html?id=LDwOAQAAMAAJ|title=America's black past|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1970}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Nat Turner|year=1971|publisher=Prentice-Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs, N.J.|isbn=978-0-13-933143-5|url=https://archive.org/details/natturner0000fone}}, editor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Nat_Turner.html?id=oTcSAAAAYAAJ|title=Nat Turner|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1971}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Tom Paine and Revolutionary America|year=1976|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-501986-5|url=https://archive.org/details/tompainerevoluti00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Tom_Paine_and_Revolutionary_America.html?id=OyFF1M8_VDAC|title=Tom Paine and Revolutionary America|isbn=978-0-19-517486-1|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2005}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Politics and Ideology in the Age of the Civil War|year=1980|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-502781-5|url=https://archive.org/details/politicsideology00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Politics_and_Ideology_in_the_Age_of_the.html?id=rQSYk-LWTxcC|title=Politics and Ideology in the Age of the Civil War|isbn=978-0-19-972708-7|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=1980-10-02}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Nothing but Freedom: Emancipation and Its Legacy|url=https://archive.org/details/nothingbutfreedo00eric|url-access=registration|year=1983|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|location=Baton Rouge|isbn=978-0-8071-1118-5}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Nothing_But_Freedom.html?id=F0ay2hkUZiwC|title=Nothing But Freedom|isbn=978-0-8071-3525-9|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=September 2007}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution, 1863\u20131877|year=1988|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-015851-4|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780060158514}} Political history; and winner, in 1989, of the [[Bancroft Prize]], the [[Francis Parkman Prize]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' Book Award, the Avery O. Craven Prize, and the Lionel Trilling Prize.\n* {{cite book|title=A Short History of Reconstruction, 1863\u20131877|year=1990|publisher=Harper & Row|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-096431-3|url=https://archive.org/details/shorthistoryofre00eric}} An abridgement of ''Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/shorthistoryofre00eric|url-access=registration|title=A Short History of Reconstruction|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=978-0-06-096431-3|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=1990-01-10}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=A House Divided: America in the Age of Lincoln|year=1990|others=with Olivia Mahoney|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|location=Chicago|isbn=978-0-393-02755-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/housedividedamer0000fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/A_House_Divided.html?id=4AO9QgAACAAJ|title=A House Divided|isbn=978-0-393-02755-6|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|last2=Mahoney|first2=Olivia|year=1990}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Reader's Companion to American History|year=1991|others=ed. with [[John A. Garraty]]|publisher=Houghton-Mifflin|location=Boston|isbn=978-0-395-51372-9|url=https://archive.org/details/readerscompanion00fone}}, editor<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/readerscompanion00fone|url-access=registration|title=The Reader's Companion to American History|publisher=Houghton-Mifflin|isbn=978-0-395-51372-9|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|last2=Garraty|first2=John Arthur|year=1991}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Tocsin of Freedom: The Black Leadership of Radical Reconstruction|year=1992|publisher=Gettysburg College|location=Gettysburg, Pa.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Tocsin_of_Freedom.html?id=FZENogEACAAJ|title=The tocsin of freedom|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1992}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Slavery and Freedom in Nineteenth-Century America|year=1994|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-952266-8}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Slavery and Freedom in Nineteenth-Century America (Inaugural Lectures (University of Oxford)): Eric Foner: 9780199522668: Amazon.com: Books|isbn = 978-0-19-952266-8|last1 = Foner|first1 = Eric|year = 1994}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=America's Reconstruction: People and Politics After the Civil War|year=1995|others=with Olivia Mahoney|publisher=HarperPerennial|location=New York|isbn=978-0-06-055346-3|url=https://archive.org/details/americasreconstr00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/America_s_Reconstruction.html?id=YNpHv2LQ8nYC|title=America's Reconstruction|isbn=978-0-8071-2234-1|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|last2=Mahoney|first2=Olivia|date=1997-06-01}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Freedom's Lawmakers: A Directory of Black Officeholders During Reconstruction|year=1996|edition=rev.|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|location=Baton Rouge|isbn=978-0-8071-2082-8}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Freedom_s_Lawmakers.html?id=F2MYAAAAIAAJ|title=Freedom's Lawmakers|isbn=978-0-19-507406-2|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1993}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The New American History|year=1997|edition=rev.|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-1-56639-551-9}}, editor<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_New_American_History.html?id=J7hnUHplC7wC|title=The New American History|isbn=978-1-56639-552-6|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1997}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Story of American Freedom|year=1998|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-04665-6|url=https://archive.org/details/storyofamericanf00fone}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_story_of_American_freedom.html?id=oLJ1AAAAMAAJ|title=The story of American freedom|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=1994}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Who Owns History?: Rethinking the Past in a Changing World|year=2002|publisher=Hill and Wang|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8090-9704-3|url=https://archive.org/details/whoownshistoryre00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3I-Z8KW5REC&printsec=copyright#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Who Owns History?|isbn=978-1-4299-2392-7|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=2003-04-16}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Give Me Liberty!: An American History|year=2004|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-97872-8}} A survey of United States history, published with companion volumes of documents.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Give_Me_Liberty.html?id=OTGXGyeVdPEC|title=Give Me Liberty!|isbn=978-0-393-92782-5|date=2005-12-01}}</ref>\n* ''Voices of Freedom: A Documentary History'', {{ISBN|978-0-393-92503-6}} (vol. 1), and {{ISBN|978-0-393-92504-3}} (2 vols.).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Voices_of_Freedom.html?id=QQCFNwAACAAJ|title=Voices of Freedom|isbn=978-0-393-92503-6|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Voices_of_Freedom.html?id=BrTtAAAAMAAJ|title=Voices of Freedom|isbn=978-0-393-93108-2|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2008}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Forever Free: The Story of Emancipation and Reconstruction|year=2005|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-375-40259-3|url=https://archive.org/details/foreverfreestory00fone}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/foreverfreestory00fone|url-access=registration|title=Forever Free|publisher=Knopf|isbn=978-0-375-40259-3|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2005}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Our Lincoln: New Perspectives on Lincoln and his World|year=2008|publisher=[[W.W. Norton]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-06756-9|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780393067569}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Our_Lincoln.html?id=gRF-PwAACAAJ|title=Our Lincoln|isbn=978-0-393-33705-1|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|year=2009}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery|year=2010|publisher=[[W.W. Norton]]|location=New York}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Fiery_Trial_Abraham_Lincoln_and_Amer.html?id=earytjxi6pEC|title=The Fiery Trial: Abraham Lincoln and American Slavery|isbn=978-0-393-08082-7|last1=Foner|first1=Eric|date=2011-09-26}}</ref>\n* {{cite book|title=Gateway to Freedom: The Hidden History of the Underground Railroad|year=2015|publisher=[[W.W. Norton & Co.]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-24407-6|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/gatewaytofreedom0000fone|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite book|title=Battles for Freedom: The Use and Abuse of American History|year=2017|publisher=[[I.B. Tauris]]|location=|isbn=978-1-78453-769-2|pages=|url=}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Second Founding: How the Civil War and Reconstruction Remade the Constitution|year=2019|publisher=[[W. W. Norton]]|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-65258-1}}\n\nSome of his books have been translated into Portuguese, Italian, and Chinese.\n\n===Selected articles===\n* {{cite journal |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Radical Individualism in America: Revolution to Civil War |journal=Literature of Liberty |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=1\u201331 |date=July\u2013September 1978 |url=http://oll.libertyfund.org/?option=com_staticxt&staticfile=show.php%3Ftitle=909&chapter=99730&layout=html&Itemid=27 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The New View of Reconstruction |journal=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=34 |issue=6 |date=October\u2013November 1983 |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/new-view-reconstruction |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Why Is There No Socialism in the United States? |journal=[[History Workshop Journal]] |volume=17 |issue= 17|pages=57\u201380 |date=Spring 1984 |jstor=4288545 |ref=harv |doi=10.1093/hwj/17.1.57 }}\n* {{cite news|last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The South's Inner Civil War |work=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=40 |issue=2 |date=March 1989 |url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/south%E2%80%99s-inner-civil-war-0 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218233100/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/south%E2%80%99s-inner-civil-war-0 |archivedate=2013-12-18 }}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Rebel Yell |work=The Nation |date=January 27, 2000 |url=http://www.thenation.com/doc/20000214/foner}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Changing History |work=The Nation |date= September 5, 2002 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/090502nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=The Century, A Nation's Eye View |work=The Nation |date=December 10, 2002 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/121002nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Not All Freedom Is Made In America |work=The New York Times|date=April 13, 2003 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/041303nytimes.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Dare Call It Treason |work=The Nation |date=June 2, 2003 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/060203nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Diversity Over Justice |work=The Nation |date=June 26, 2003 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/072603nation.html}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Rethinking American History in a Post-9/11 World |work=History News Network |date=September 6, 2004 |url=http://ericfoner.com/articles/090604hnn.html}}\n* {{cite web|last=Foner |first=Eric |title=Expert Report of Eric Foner: from Gratz, et al. v. Bollinger, et al. |url=http://www.vpcomm.umich.edu/admissions/legal/expert/foner.html |date=2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060829030100/http://www.vpcomm.umich.edu/admissions/legal/expert/foner.html |archivedate=August 29, 2006}}\n* {{cite news |last=Foner |first=Eric |title=He's the Worst Ever |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 3, 2006 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/01/AR2006120101509.html}} Column on George W. Bush.\n* {{cite news |