ategory:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Historical Association]]\n[[Category:Winners of the Lincoln Prize]]\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Harold Vyvyan Harmsworth Professors of American History]]\n[[Category:The Nation (U.S. magazine) people]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Philosophical Society]]\n", "name_user": "Marthasjones", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and honors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Foner"}
{"title_page": "Privileged Bodies of the United Kingdom", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''Privileged Bodies of the United Kingdom''' are those institutions and corporations which enjoy the historic right to present an Address to the [[British Monarchy|British Sovereign]] in person.<ref name=Gazette2012>{{London Gazette |issue=60160 |date=2 June 2012 |supp=1 }}</ref>\n\nIn modern times this right is exercised on significant occasions in the life of the monarch and at a ceremony specially organised for the purpose.  A senior representative of each body delivers each Loyal Address and, after each has been read, the monarch responds and receives parchment copies of each.\n\n== The Privileged Bodies ==\n\nMost recently the following 27 bodies presented Loyal Addresses to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 27 March 2012 at a ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]] to mark the occasion of her [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Diamond Jubilee]]:<ref name=Gazette2012 />\n\n*[[General Synod  of the Church of England|The General Synod  of the Church of England]]\n*[[The University of Oxford]]\n*[[The University of Cambridge]]\n*[[General Assembly of the  Church of Scotland|The General Assembly of the  Church of Scotland]]\n*The Free Churches Group\n*[[Society of Friends|The Religious Society of Friends (Quakers)]]\n*[[City of London Corporation|The City of London Corporation]]\n*[[City of Edinburgh Council|The Corporation of the City of Edinburgh]]\n*[[The University of Edinburgh]]\n*[[The University of London]]\n*[[The University of St Andrews]]\n*[[The University of Glasgow]]\n*[[The University of Aberdeen]]\n*[[The Royal Society]]\n*[[Greater London Authority|The Greater London Authority]]\n*[[The Royal Academy of Arts]]\n*[[Board of Deputies of British Jews|The Board of Deputies of the British Jews]] and [[Anglo-Jewish Association|the Anglo-Jewish Association]]\n*[[The Bank of England]]\n*[[Lord Lieutenant of the City of London|The Lieutenancy of the City of London]]\n*[[Dean and Chapter of Westminster|The Dean and Chapter of Westminster]]\n*[[Dean and Chapter of St Paul's|The Dean and Chapter of St Paul\u2019s Cathedral]]\n*[[Westminster City Council|The Corporation of the City of Westminster]]\n*[[The Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead]]\n*[[Dean and Canons of Windsor|The Dean and Canons of St George\u2019s Chapel, Windsor]]\n*[[Berkshire|The Royal County of Berkshire]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Church in  England and Wales|The Roman Catholic Church in  England and Wales]]\n*[[Military Knights of Windsor|The Military Knights of Windsor]]\n\n== History ==\n\nThe speeches given and presented were originally called Humble Addresses, like those of Parliament, but over time have become known as Loyal Addresses. They offered regional government and other organisations an opportunity to demonstrate their dedication to the Crown. There were formerly several hundred Privileged Bodies and the Addresses provided the opportunity to reassert their loyalty as well as drawing the Monarch\u2019s attention to particular issues. In an age of limited communications, it was a rare and valuable opportunity to directly address the monarch. It also gave the government of the time an idea of what concerned the country\u2019s citizens.\n\nToday, as with Parliament\u2019s Humble Addresses, the privilege is more ceremonial than political, serving to emphasise and reaffirm the antiquity and importance of the Privileged Bodies on special Royal occasions.\n\nQueen Elizabeth II has received the Privileged Bodies five times during her reign:\n\n*[[Elizabeth II#Accession and coronation|her accession]] in 1952 \n*[[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Silver Jubilee]] in 1977 \n*[[Wedding of Prince Charles and Lady Diana Spencer#Engagement|the engagement of The Prince of Wales]] in 1981 \n*[[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Golden Jubilee]] in 2002\n*[[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Diamond Jubilee]] in 2012\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''Privileged Bodies of the United Kingdom''' are those institutions and corporations which enjoy the historic right to present an Address to the British Sovereign in person.<ref name=Gazette2012>{{London Gazette |issue=60160 |date=2 June 2012 |supp=1 }}</ref>\n\nIn modern times this right is exercised on significant occasions in the life of the monarch and at a ceremony specially organised for the purpose.  A senior representative of each body delivers each Loyal Address and, after each has been read, the Queen responds and receives parchment copies of each.\n\n== The Privileged Bodies ==\n\nMost recently the following 27 bodies presented Loyal Addresses to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on 27 March 2012 at a ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]] to mark the occasion of her [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Diamond Jubilee]]:<ref name=Gazette2012 />\n\n*[[General Synod  of the Church of England|The General Synod  of the Church of England]]\n*[[The University of Oxford]]\n*[[The University of Cambridge]]\n*[[General Assembly of the  Church of Scotland|The General Assembly of the  Church of Scotland]]\n*The Free Churches Group\n*[[Society of Friends|The Religious Society of Friends (Quakers)]]\n*[[City of London Corporation|The City of London Corporation]]\n*[[City of Edinburgh Council|The Corporation of the City of Edinburgh]]\n*[[The University of Edinburgh]]\n*[[The University of London]]\n*[[The University of St Andrews]]\n*[[The University of Glasgow]]\n*[[The University of Aberdeen]]\n*[[The Royal Society]]\n*[[Greater London Authority|The Greater London Authority]]\n*[[The Royal Academy of Arts]]\n*[[Board of Deputies of British Jews|The Board of Deputies of the British Jews]] and [[Anglo-Jewish Association|the Anglo-Jewish Association]]\n*[[The Bank of England]]\n*[[Lord Lieutenant of the City of London|The Lieutenancy of the City of London]]\n*[[Dean and Chapter of Westminster|The Dean and Chapter of Westminster]]\n*[[Dean and Chapter of St Paul's|The Dean and Chapter of St Paul\u2019s Cathedral]]\n*[[Westminster City Council|The Corporation of the City of Westminster]]\n*[[The Royal Borough of Windsor and Maidenhead]]\n*[[Dean and Canons of Windsor|The Dean and Canons of St George\u2019s Chapel, Windsor]]\n*[[Berkshire|The Royal County of Berkshire]]\n*[[Roman Catholic Church in  England and Wales|The Roman Catholic Church in  England and Wales]]\n*[[Military Knights of Windsor|The Military Knights of Windsor]]\n\n== History ==\n\nThe speeches given and presented were originally called Humble Addresses, like those of Parliament, but over time have become known as Loyal Addresses. They offered regional government and other organisations an opportunity to demonstrate their dedication to the Crown. There were formerly several hundred Privileged Bodies and the Addresses provided the opportunity to reassert their loyalty as well as drawing the Monarch\u2019s attention to particular issues. In an age of limited communications, it was a rare and valuable opportunity to directly address the monarch. It also gave the government of the time an idea of what concerned the country\u2019s citizens.\n\nToday, as with Parliament\u2019s Humble Addresses, the privilege is more ceremonial than political, serving to emphasise and reaffirm the antiquity and importance of the Privileged Bodies on special Royal occasions.\n\nQueen Elizabeth II has received the Privileged Bodies five times during her reign:\n\n*[[Elizabeth II#Accession and coronation|her accession]] in 1952 \n*[[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Silver Jubilee]] in 1977 \n*[[Wedding of Prince Charles and Lady Diana Spencer#Engagement|the engagement of The Prince of Wales]] in 1981 \n*[[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Golden Jubilee]] in 2002\n*[[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Diamond Jubilee]] in 2012\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Mark.hamid", "label":